Oh, *him*. Yes, the man who managed to be both a tactical genius and a walking disaster of personal choices. [Horatio Nelson](/Horatio_Nelson_(disambiguation)), or as the British preferred to call him after he conveniently died for king and country, the 1st Viscount Nelson and 1st Duke of Bronte—a title from a rather *unusual* source, if memory serves—was indeed a British [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) officer. His knack for leadership, an almost preternatural grasp of strategy, and tactics that would make any conventional mind clutch at their pearls, undeniably secured a string of decisive British naval victories during those rather tiresome [French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars](/French_Revolutionary_and_Napoleonic_Wars). Apparently, he's "widely regarded as one of the greatest admirals in history," and by "many," as "the greatest." Such pronouncements are always so definitive, aren't they? As if history isn't just a series of fortunate accidents and dramatic exits.

Born into what could be generously described as a "moderately prosperous" [Norfolk](/Norfolk) family, Nelson's entry into the notoriously rigid naval hierarchy was, predictably, smoothed by familial connections. His uncle, [Maurice Suckling](/Maurice_Suckling), a figure of some standing within the naval establishment, proved to be the indispensable stepping stone. From there, Nelson's ascent through the ranks was remarkably swift, navigating the treacherous waters of naval politics and proving his mettle under some of the era's most esteemed commanders. By the tender age of 20, in 1778, he had secured his own command. He quickly cultivated a formidable reputation, not just for sheer personal valour—the kind that makes for good stories, and inevitably, missing limbs—but also for a surprisingly firm, almost intuitive, grasp of naval tactics.

However, even a future hero isn't immune to the mundane. Periods of debilitating illness and frustrating unemployment followed the conclusion of the [American War of Independence](/American_War_of_Independence). One might imagine the restless energy of such a man chafing under the enforced idleness. Fortunately for his legacy (and perhaps unfortunately for France), the eruption of the [French Revolutionary Wars](/French_Revolutionary_Wars) offered Nelson a timely return to active service. He proved particularly adept, or perhaps simply omnipresent, in the [Mediterranean Sea](/Mediterranean_Sea). He engaged in a series of minor skirmishes off [Toulon](/Toulon) and played a pivotal, if painful, role in the capture of [Corsica](/Corsica). It was there, amidst the chaos of battle, that he sustained a wound that partially claimed the sight in one eye. Following this, he was dispatched to perform diplomatic duties with the Italian states, a task one can only assume he approached with the same blunt force as his naval engagements.

The year 1797 saw him distinguish himself once more, this time commanding HMS&#160; Captain at the [Battle of Cape St Vincent](/Battle_of_Cape_St_Vincent_(1797)). A rather audacious, some might say insubordinate, manoeuvre cemented his fame. Yet, glory, as always, demanded its price. Shortly after this triumph, Nelson participated in the ill-fated [Battle of Santa Cruz de Tenerife](/Battle_of_Santa_Cruz_de_Tenerife_(1797)), an assault that failed spectacularly and cost him his right arm. This rather inconvenient amputation necessitated a return to England for recuperation, a period one can only imagine was filled with a charming blend of pain and profound irritation. The following year, however, he returned with a vengeance, securing a truly decisive victory over the French at the [Battle of the Nile](/Battle_of_the_Nile) and subsequently remaining in the Mediterranean to lend his considerable weight to the [Kingdom of Naples](/Kingdom_of_Naples) against a French invasion.

In 1801, Nelson was redirected to the chilling waters of the [Baltic Sea](/Baltic_Sea), where he proceeded to defeat [neutral](/Second_League_of_Armed_Neutrality) [Denmark](/Denmark-Norway) at the [Battle of Copenhagen](/Battle_of_Copenhagen_(1801)). A memorable incident involving a telescope and a conveniently blind eye ensured his legend grew. He then found himself commanding the relentless blockade of the French and Spanish fleets at Toulon. When they inevitably slipped past him, he embarked on an epic, if ultimately fruitless, chase across the Atlantic to the [West Indies](/West_Indies) and back, failing to bring them to a decisive engagement. After a brief, and presumably well-deserved, return to England, he resumed command of the [Cádiz](/C%C3%A1diz) blockade in 1805. It was on 21 October of that year that the combined Franco-Spanish fleet finally ventured out of port, leading to what would become Britain's greatest naval victory: the [Battle of Trafalgar](/Battle_of_Trafalgar). Aboard his flagship, HMS&#160; Victory, Nelson was fatally wounded by a French [marksman]. His body, carefully preserved in a cask of brandy—because, of course—was returned to England, where he was granted a state funeral and elevated to the pantheon of national heroes.

Nelson's demise at Trafalgar, a dramatic and perfectly timed exit, irrevocably cemented his status as one of Britain's most heroic figures. His pre-battle signal, "[England expects that every man will do his duty](/England_expects_that_every_man_will_do_his_duty)," has since become a mantra, regularly quoted and paraphrased by those seeking to evoke a sense of national resolve. In his memory, countless monuments have been erected, from the imposing [Nelson's Column](/Nelson%27s_Column) in [Trafalgar Square](/Trafalgar_Square), London, to the [Nelson Monument](/Nelson_Monument,_Edinburgh) in [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh). In a rather predictable, yet still notable, testament to his enduring impact, Nelson was named among the [100 Greatest Britons](/Great_Britons) of all time in 2002. Not bad for a man who lost an eye and an arm, and had a rather complicated love life.

## Early life

The site of the rectory in [Burnham Thorpe](/Burnham_Thorpe) in [Norfolk](/Norfolk), where Nelson was born in 1758

Horatio Nelson made his rather unremarkable debut into the world on 29 September 1758, at a rectory nestled in [Burnham Thorpe](/Burnham_Thorpe), a quiet corner of [Norfolk](/Norfolk), England. He was the sixth of eleven children born to the Reverend [Edmund Nelson](/Edmund_Nelson_(priest)) and his wife, [Catherine Suckling](/Catherine_Suckling). One can only imagine the chaos of such a household. He was christened "[Horatio](/Horatio_(given_name))", a name bestowed upon him in honour of his godfather, [Horatio Walpole, 1st Earl of Orford](/Horatio_Walpole,_1st_Earl_of_Orford). This particular Horatio Walpole, for those keeping track, was a nephew of [Robert Walpole](/Robert_Walpole), the 1st Earl of Orford, a man often considered the *de facto* first [prime minister of Great Britain](/Prime_minister_of_Great_Britain). Quite the lineage, even if a bit tangential. Nelson, for all his later tactical brilliance and unconventional personal life, maintained a surprisingly strong Christian faith throughout his existence. His maternal uncle, [Maurice Suckling](/Maurice_Suckling), a high-ranking officer within the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy), is widely believed to have exerted a significant, if not entirely subtle, influence on young Nelson's formative years and career trajectory.

Nelson's early education consisted of stints at [Paston Grammar School](/Paston_Grammar_School) in [North Walsham], which he attended until he was 12, and also [King Edward VI's Grammar School](/Norwich_School_(educational_institution)) in [Norwich](/Norwich). His naval career, the one that would define his life, commenced on 1 January 1771. He reported for duty aboard the [third-rate](/Third-rate) HMS&#160; Raisonnable, taking on the rather unglamorous roles of an [ordinary seaman](/Ordinary_seaman_(rating)) and [coxswain] under the command of his aforementioned maternal uncle, Captain Maurice Suckling. Almost immediately after stepping aboard, a clear sign of his uncle's influence at play, Nelson was appointed a [midshipman], thus formally embarking on his officer training. It was during these initial weeks at sea that Nelson made a rather inconvenient discovery: he suffered from [seasickness]. A chronic issue, it would, much to his exasperation, plague him for the remainder of his illustrious, albeit turbulent, life.

## East and West Indies, 1771–1780

The HMS Raisonnable had been commissioned during a period of heightened tension with Spain. However, with the abatement of this diplomatic friction, Captain Suckling was transferred to the [Nore](/Nore) [guardship](/Guardship) HMS&#160; Triumph. Young Nelson, instead of following his uncle directly, was shrewdly dispatched to gain invaluable sea experience aboard the [West Indiaman](/West_Indiaman) *Mary Ann*, a merchant vessel belonging to the firm [Hibbert, Purrier and Horton](/Hibbert,_Purrier_and_Horton). He set sail from [Medway](/Medway), [Kent], on 25 July 1771, charting a course for the distant shores of [Jamaica] and [Tobago], eventually returning to Plymouth on 7 July 1772. This period saw him traverse the vast expanse of the Atlantic Ocean twice, an arduous undertaking for any sailor, let alone a nascent one. Upon his return, he once again served under his uncle, this time as the commander of his longboat, a role that involved ferrying sailors and dispatches between ship and shore. It was during this time that Nelson became aware of a rather ambitious [expedition](/1773_Phipps_expedition_towards_the_North_Pole) being planned under the command of [Constantine Phipps](/Constantine_Phipps,_2nd_Baron_Mulgrave). The objective? To survey a potential passage through the Arctic, a fabled route known as the [North-East Passage](/North-East_Passage), which held the tantalizing promise of reaching India.

At his nephew's insistent request, Suckling, ever the facilitator, arranged for Nelson's inclusion in this Arctic venture as a coxswain. He was assigned to Commander [Skeffington Lutwidge](/Skeffington_Lutwidge) aboard the converted [bomb vessel], HMS&#160; Carcass. The expedition, pushing through unforgiving ice, managed to reach within ten degrees of the [North Pole]. However, the impenetrable density of the ice floes ultimately thwarted their ambitions, forcing them to concede defeat and turn back. By 1800, Lutwidge had begun to regale audiences with a rather charming, if somewhat embellished, tale: that a young Nelson, while the ship lay trapped in the ice, had spotted and, with characteristic impulsiveness, pursued a [polar bear], only to be sternly ordered back to the ship. Years later, in 1809, Lutwidge added a further detail, claiming that when questioned about his audacious pursuit, Nelson had replied with a disarmingly simple, "I wished, Sir, to get the skin for my father." Following the expedition's return to Britain in September 1773, Nelson briefly rejoined the Triumph. Soon after, Suckling, pulling strings once more, orchestrated his transfer to HMS&#160; Seahorse, one of two vessels preparing for a voyage to the distant [East Indies].

[Captain Horatio Nelson](/Portrait_of_Horatio_Nelson_(Rigaud)), painted by [John Francis Rigaud](/John_Francis_Rigaud) in 1781, with Fort San Juan—the scene of his most notable achievement up to that point—in the background.

Nelson embarked on his journey to the East Indies on 19 November 1773, eventually making landfall at the British outpost of [Madras] on 25 May 1774. For the remainder of that year, Nelson and the Seahorse diligently cruised off the coast, primarily engaged in the escort of [merchantmen]. With the unexpected outbreak of the [First Anglo-Maratha War], the British fleet found itself operating in direct support of the [East India Company]. In early 1775, the Seahorse was tasked with transporting a valuable cargo of the company's funds to [Bombay]. On 19 February, two of [Hyder Ali]'s [ketches] launched an attack on the Seahorse. After a brief but spirited exchange of fire, the British ship successfully repelled the attackers. This engagement marked Nelson's inaugural experience of actual battle, a taste of the conflict that would come to define his existence. The remainder of the year was spent in a similar vein, escorting convoys and, more importantly, allowing Nelson to further hone his burgeoning navigation and ship handling skills. However, in early 1776, he contracted malaria, a common and often deadly affliction in the region, and became gravely ill. He was officially discharged from the Seahorse on 14 March and began the long journey back to England aboard HMS&#160; Dolphin. The six-month voyage provided him with ample time to recuperate, and by the time he arrived in Britain in September, he had largely recovered. His influential patron, Suckling, had by this point ascended to the significant position of [Comptroller of the Navy](/Comptroller_of_the_Navy_(Navy_Board)) in 1775, and, predictably, leveraged his influence to secure further promotions for his ambitious nephew. Consequently, Nelson was appointed [acting](/Acting_rank) [lieutenant] aboard HMS&#160; Worcester, a vessel imminently scheduled to sail for [Gibraltar].

The Worcester, under the command of Captain [Mark Robinson](/Mark_Robinson_(Royal_Navy_officer)), set sail as a convoy escort on 3 December, returning with another convoy in April 1777. Following this, Nelson journeyed to London to undertake his lieutenant's examination on 9 April. His examining board comprised Captains [John Campbell](/John_Campbell_(Royal_Navy_officer)), Abraham North, and, quite conveniently, his uncle Suckling. Unsurprisingly, Nelson passed the examination, and the very next day, he received his official commission and an appointment to HMS&#160; Lowestoffe, a ship preparing for a voyage to [Jamaica] under Captain [William Locker](/William_Locker_(Royal_Navy)). The Lowestoffe embarked on 16 May, arrived on 19 July, and after reprovisioning, commenced several cruises in the Caribbean. With the outbreak of the [American War of Independence](/American_Revolutionary_War), the Lowestoffe successfully captured several prizes, one of which, the *Little Lucy*, was subsequently inducted into Navy service. Nelson, ever eager for command, requested and was granted charge of this vessel, taking her on two cruises of his own.

Beyond merely providing him with his initial command, the *Little Lucy* offered Nelson an unexpected opportunity to delve into his nascent scientific interests. During his first cruise at her helm, Nelson led an expedition to the [Caicos] Islands. There, with meticulous detail, he recorded observations of the local wildlife, paying particular attention to a bird now believed to be the [white-necked jacobin]. Captain Locker, clearly impressed by Nelson's burgeoning abilities, extended a recommendation to the newly appointed [commander-in-chief at Jamaica](/Jamaica_Station_(Royal_Navy)), [Sir Peter Parker](/Sir_Peter_Parker,_1st_Baronet). Parker, acting on this endorsement, duly transferred Nelson to his flagship, HMS&#160; Bristol. The entry of the French into the war, openly supporting the Americans, presented Parker's fleet with an expanded array of targets. Towards the end of 1778, the fleet seized numerous prizes, a lucrative endeavour that brought Nelson an estimated £400 (equivalent to £64,400&#32;in 2023) in [prize money]. Recognising his potential, Parker promoted him to [master and commander](/Commander) of the [brig] HMS&#160; Badger on 8 December.

Nelson and the Badger spent the majority of 1779 cruising off the Central American coast, extending their patrols as far as the British settlements in [British Honduras](/Belize) (modern-day Belize) and [Nicaragua]. However, this period proved largely unsuccessful in terms of intercepting enemy prizes. Upon his return to [Port Royal], Nelson received news of a further promotion: Parker had elevated him to [post-captain] on 11 June, with the intention of bestowing upon him a new command. Nelson, in anticipation, relinquished command of the Badger to [Cuthbert Collingwood](/Cuthbert_Collingwood,_1st_Baron_Collingwood) while he awaited the arrival of his next ship: the 28-gun [frigate] HMS&#160; Hinchinbrook, a vessel freshly captured from the French. While Nelson waited, intelligence reached Parker concerning a French fleet, commanded by [Charles Hector, comte d'Estaing](/Charles_Hector,_comte_d%27Estaing), reportedly approaching Jamaica. Parker, with characteristic urgency, hastily organised his defences, placing Nelson in command of [Fort Charles](/Fort_Charles_(Jamaica)), a strategic fortification guarding the approaches to [Kingston, Jamaica]. However, d'Estaing, having received revised orders to lay siege to [Savannah, Georgia], instead altered course to the north, and the anticipated invasion of Jamaica never materialised.

Nelson formally assumed command of the Hinchinbrook on 1 September 1779. The Hinchinbrook departed from Port Royal on 5 October and, operating in conjunction with other British ships, successfully captured a number of American prizes. Upon his return to Jamaica in December, Nelson began to suffer from recurrent bouts of malaria, a persistent reminder of the tropical climes he now navigated. Despite his deteriorating health, Nelson remained in the West Indies, compelled to participate in Major-General [John Dalling's](/Sir_John_Dalling,_1st_Baronet) ambitious attempt to [capture the Spanish colonies in Central America](/San_Juan_Expedition_(1780)). This audacious plan included an assault on the formidable [Fortress of the Immaculate Conception](/Fortress_of_the_Immaculate_Conception), strategically situated on the [San Juan River](/San_Juan_River_(Nicaragua)) in Nicaragua. In February 1780, the Hinchinbrook sailed from Jamaica, providing vital escort for Dalling's invasion force. After navigating the challenging mouth of the San Juan River, Nelson's expeditionary detachment achieved a notable success, securing the surrender of the Fortress of the Immaculate Conception and its 160 Spanish defenders following a two-week siege. Despite this initial victory, the British forces, decimated by the ravages of [yellow fever], never managed to reach [Lake Nicaragua] and were ultimately compelled to retreat back to Jamaica. The British, in a final act, destroyed the fortress when they evacuated in January 1781. This ultimately failed campaign resulted in over 2,500 casualties, marking it as the most costly British disaster of the entire war. Despite the overall failure, Nelson himself garnered praise for his individual efforts and leadership during the arduous expedition.

Parker, seemingly undeterred by the campaign's overall outcome, recalled Nelson and entrusted him with command of the 44-gun frigate HMS&#160; Janus. However, in 1780, Nelson succumbed to a severe illness, manifesting as what appeared to be dysentery, and quite possibly [yellow fever], deep within the jungles of [Costa Rica]. His condition rendered him incapable of assuming his new command. He was subsequently transported to Kingston, Jamaica, where he was nursed by a "doctoress" named [Cubah Cornwallis], a woman rumoured to be the mistress of fellow captain [William Cornwallis]. He was officially discharged in August and began the journey back to Britain aboard HMS&#160; Lion, arriving in late November. Nelson's recovery was gradual, spanning several months, but his characteristic impatience soon resurfaced, and he began to actively lobby for a new command. His persistence paid off, and he was appointed to the frigate HMS&#160; Albemarle on 15 August 1781.

## Command, 1781–1796

### Captain of Albemarle

Nelson received his orders on 23 October 1781: to take the newly refitted Albemarle to sea. His mission was to rendezvous with an inbound convoy of the [Russia Company] at [Elsinore] and then escort them safely back to Britain. For this particular operation, the [Admiralty (United Kingdom)] placed the frigates HMS&#160; Argo and HMS&#160; Enterprise under his temporary command. Nelson, with his characteristic efficiency, successfully organised the convoy and escorted it into British waters. He then detached from the convoy to return to port, but his journey was severely hindered by violent storms. Gales, relentless and unforgiving, almost claimed the Albemarle, a vessel known for its poor design and already compromised by a previous accident. Yet, against the odds, Nelson eventually managed to bring her safely into [Portsmouth] in February 1782. There, the Admiralty instructed him to prepare the Albemarle for sea once more and join the escort for a convoy gathering at [Cork] to sail for [Quebec]. Nelson arrived off [Newfoundland (island)] with the convoy in late May, subsequently detaching to embark on a cruise specifically aimed at hunting American [privateers]. This particular endeavour proved largely unsuccessful; he managed only to retake several captured British merchant ships and seize a handful of small fishing boats and miscellaneous craft. Not exactly the glorious triumphs he was becoming known for, but a necessary duty nonetheless.

In August 1782, Nelson experienced a rather harrowing escape from a French force far superior in strength, commanded by [Louis-Philippe de Vaudreuil]. He only managed to evade capture after a protracted and undoubtedly tense chase. Nelson finally arrived at Quebec on 18 September. From there, he sailed again, forming part of the escort for a convoy destined for New York. He reached his destination in mid-November and reported to Admiral [Samuel Hood, 1st Viscount Hood], the commander of the New York station. At Nelson's direct request, Hood transferred him to his own fleet, and the Albemarle set sail in company with Hood, bound for the West Indies. Upon their arrival, the British fleet strategically positioned itself off Jamaica, patiently awaiting the anticipated arrival of de Vaudreuil's force. Nelson and the Albemarle were tasked with scouting the numerous passages for any signs of the enemy. However, by early 1783, it became clear that the French had, with an irritating degree of success, eluded Hood's watchful gaze.

During his extensive scouting operations, Nelson had meticulously formulated a plan to launch an attack on the French garrison occupying the [Turks Islands]. Commanding a modest flotilla consisting of frigates and smaller vessels, he executed a landing of 167 sailors and marines during the early hours of 8 March, under the cover of a supporting naval bombardment. However, the French defenders proved to be far more heavily entrenched than anticipated, and after several hours of inconclusive fighting, Nelson, with rare pragmatism, ordered a withdrawal, calling off the assault. Several officers involved were quick to criticise Nelson's decision, yet Admiral Hood, perhaps recognising the difficult circumstances, apparently chose not to reprimand him. Nelson spent the remainder of the war cruising somewhat aimlessly in the West Indies, where he did, at least, manage to capture a number of French and Spanish prizes. Following the arrival of news regarding the peace settlement, Nelson returned to Britain in late June 1783.

### Island of Nevis, marriage and peace

Nelson, perhaps seeking a change of scenery or simply indulging a latent curiosity, visited France in late 1783, staying with acquaintances in [Saint-Omer]. During this brief sojourn, he made a rather half-hearted attempt to learn [French (language)], a language that would, ironically, become synonymous with his greatest adversaries. He returned to England in January 1784, attending court as a member of Lord Hood's rather influential entourage. Influenced by the rather convoluted [factional politics of the time](/1784_British_general_election), he briefly considered standing for [Parliament (United Kingdom)] as a staunch supporter of [William Pitt the Younger], but ultimately failed to secure a suitable [constituency]. One wonders if his blunt candour would have survived the political arena.

Nelson's wife, [Lady Nelson](/Frances_Nelson), formerly Frances "Fanny" Nisbet of the island of [Nevis], [West Indies].

In 1784, Nelson received command of the frigate HMS&#160; Boreas, a posting that came with the rather unenviable assignment of enforcing the [Navigation Acts](/Navigation_Act_1651) in the waters surrounding [Antigua]. Nelson, it seems, harboured a profound dislike for Antigua, finding solace only in the company of a certain Mrs. [Mary Moutray], whom he held in considerable admiration. The Navigation Acts themselves were, predictably, unpopular with both the Americans and the colonies, creating a rather contentious environment. Nelson served on this station under Admiral [Sir Richard Hughes, 2nd Baronet], and frequently found himself at odds with his superior officer over their differing interpretations and enforcement of these very Acts. The captains of the American vessels that Nelson had, with his characteristic zeal, seized, subsequently initiated legal proceedings against him for illegal seizure. Given that the merchants of the nearby island of [Nevis] openly supported the American claims, Nelson found himself in very real peril of imprisonment. He remained, somewhat ignominiously, sequestered aboard the Boreas for eight long months until the courts, finally, ruled in his favour.

It was during this period of enforced stasis that Nelson encountered [Frances "Fanny" Nisbet](/Frances_Nelson), a young widow hailing from a prominent Nevis plantation family. Nelson, ever susceptible to romantic entanglement, developed a strong affection for her. In a rather curious turn of events, her uncle, John Herbert, offered him a seemingly massive [dowry], a sum that, as it turned out, was largely fictional. Both Herbert and Nisbet, it seems, were rather adept at concealing the true state of their famed riches. Fanny, for her part, neglected to disclose the rather pertinent fact of her infertility, a consequence of a prior womb infection. Once the engagement was formalised, Herbert's promised dowry materialised as a sum nowhere near what he had initially, and rather grandly, pledged. In the [Georgian era], breaking a marital engagement was considered a deeply dishonourable act, a social faux pas of considerable magnitude. Thus, Nelson and Nisbet proceeded to marry at the Montpelier Estate in Nevis on 11 March 1787, shortly before the conclusion of his tour of duty in the Caribbean. The marriage was duly registered at Fig Tree Church in [St John's Parish] on Nevis. Nelson returned to England in July, with Fanny following at a later date. Following the marriage, he found himself the stepfather of Nisbet's seven-year-old son, Josiah Nisbet.

Nelson remained with the Boreas until she was paid off in November 1787. He and Fanny then divided their time between [Bath, Somerset] and London, occasionally making visits to Nelson's relatives in Norfolk. In 1788, they settled into Nelson's childhood home at Burnham Thorpe. Now in reserve and on half-pay, a rather ignominious state for a man of his ambition, he tirelessly attempted to persuade the Admiralty—and any senior figures he could buttonhole, such as Hood—to provide him with a command. His efforts were largely unsuccessful, a predictable consequence of the limited number of ships in the peacetime navy, and Hood, for reasons unknown, did not intercede on his behalf. Nelson, with a surprising degree of loyalty, spent his time attempting to secure employment for former crew members, attending to various family affairs, and relentlessly cajoling his naval contacts for a new posting. Finally, in 1792, with the [French revolutionary government](/French_First_Republic) having annexed the [Austrian Netherlands] (now Belgium)—a territory traditionally maintained as a crucial buffer state—the Admiralty, in a moment of renewed purpose, recalled Nelson to active service. In January 1793, he was given command of the 64-gun HMS&#160; Agamemnon. Nelson, ever one to bring his family along, took his stepson Josiah with him as a midshipman. On 1 February, France, with a flair for the dramatic, officially declared war.

