In May 1793, Nelson, aboard the Agamemnon, sailed as an integral part of a division under the command of Vice Admiral [William Hotham, 1st Baron Hotham]. This force was subsequently augmented later that month by the arrival of the remainder of Lord Hood's fleet. The combined British force initially set a course for Gibraltar, with the overarching strategic objective of establishing unequivocal naval superiority in the [Mediterranean]. From Gibraltar, they proceeded to [Toulon], eventually anchoring off the port in July. Toulon itself was a city in flux, largely under the control of moderate republicans and [royalists], but simultaneously menaced by the advancing forces of the [National Convention]. Faced with dwindling supplies and harbouring serious doubts about their capacity for self-defence, the city authorities made a rather desperate plea, requesting that Hood take Toulon under British protection. Hood, ever the opportunist, readily assented, and promptly dispatched Nelson to carry dispatches—urgent requests for reinforcements—to [Sardinia] and [Naples]. After successfully delivering the dispatches to Sardinia, the Agamemnon arrived at Naples in early September. There, Nelson was introduced to King [Ferdinand IV of Naples], followed by a meeting with the British ambassador to the kingdom, [William Hamilton (diplomat)]. It was during these crucial negotiations for reinforcements that Nelson, with an almost fated timing, was introduced to Hamilton's new, rather captivating wife, [Emma, Lady Hamilton].

The negotiations, perhaps surprisingly, proved successful, and by mid-September, a considerable force of 2,000 sailors and several ships had been mustered. Nelson, ever restless, immediately put to sea in pursuit of a French frigate. Upon failing to intercept her, he altered course for [Leghorn] and subsequently Corsica. He arrived back at Toulon on 5 October, only to find a large French army having occupied the strategic hills surrounding the city, relentlessly bombarding it. Hood, clinging to a fading hope, still believed the city could be held if further reinforcements arrived, and thus sent Nelson to join a squadron operating off [Cagliari].

### Corsica

•
See also: [Invasion of Corsica (1794)](/Invasion_of_Corsica_(1794))

In the early hours of 22 October 1793, the Agamemnon sighted five sails on the horizon. Nelson, never one to hesitate, promptly closed with them, quickly discerning they constituted a French squadron. He immediately gave chase, opening fire on the 40-gun *Melpomene*. During the ensuing [action of 22 October 1793], he inflicted considerable damage. However, the remaining French ships, sensing an opportunity, turned to join the fray. Realising he was significantly outnumbered, Nelson, with a rare display of tactical prudence, withdrew and continued his course to Cagliari, arriving on 24 October. After undertaking necessary repairs, Nelson and the Agamemnon set sail for [Tunis] on 26 October, joining a squadron under Commodore [Robert Linzee]. Upon arrival, Nelson was entrusted with command of a small squadron himself, comprising the Agamemnon, three frigates, and a sloop, with orders to establish a blockade of the French garrison on Corsica. The fall of Toulon at the end of December 1793 dealt a severe blow to British fortunes in the Mediterranean. Hood, in a rather glaring oversight, had failed to make adequate provisions for a withdrawal, resulting in a staggering 18 French [ships-of-the-line] falling into republican hands. Consequently, Nelson's mission to Corsica acquired significantly added importance, as the island could potentially provide the British with a much-needed naval base strategically close to the French coast. Hood, understanding the gravity of the situation, therefore reinforced Nelson with additional ships in January 1794.

A British assault force made landfall on the island on 7 February, after which Nelson, with renewed vigour, moved to intensify the blockade off [Bastia]. For the remainder of that month, he conducted a series of raids along the coast and successfully intercepted enemy shipping. By late February, [San Fiorenzo had fallen](/Siege_of_San_Fiorenzo), and British troops, under the command of Lieutenant-General [David Dundas (British Army officer)], had advanced into the outskirts of Bastia. However, Dundas, after merely assessing the enemy positions, inexplicably withdrew, arguing that the French were too well entrenched to risk a direct assault. Nelson, with characteristic persuasive force, managed to convince Hood otherwise. Yet, a protracted and undoubtedly frustrating debate between the army and naval commanders meant that Nelson did not receive official permission to proceed until late March. Undeterred, Nelson began the arduous task of landing guns from his ships and meticulously emplacing them in the strategic hills surrounding the town. On 11 April, the British squadron boldly entered the harbour and opened fire, while Nelson, ever at the forefront, personally assumed command of the land forces and commenced the bombardment. After a relentless 45-day siege, the town finally surrendered. Nelson then immediately set about preparing for an assault on [Calvi], working in close cooperation with Lieutenant-General [Charles Stuart (1753–1801)].

British forces made their landing at Calvi on 19 June, and with swift efficiency, immediately began the arduous process of moving guns ashore to occupy the commanding heights surrounding the town. While Nelson, with his usual intensity, directed a continuous bombardment of the entrenched enemy positions, Stuart's soldiers steadily advanced. On the morning of 12 July, Nelson found himself at one of the forward batteries when a shot, seemingly from nowhere, struck one of the nearby sandbags providing protection for the position, sending a shower of stones and sand flying. Nelson was struck by this debris in his right eye, a painful injury that forced him to temporarily retire from his post. However, his wound was swiftly bandaged, and with remarkable resilience, he returned to action. By 18 July, the majority of the enemy positions had been neutralised, and that night, Stuart, with Nelson's unwavering support, stormed the main defensive position and successfully captured it. Repositioning their guns, the British brought Calvi under a relentless and constant bombardment, forcing the town to surrender on 10 August. Nelson did, eventually, regain partial sight in his damaged eye, though he famously remarked he could only "...distinguish light from dark but no object." A rather grim souvenir, one might say.

### Genoa and the fight of the Ça Ira

•
Main article: [Battle of Genoa (1795)](/Battle_of_Genoa_(1795))

The fight of the Ça Ira

Following the successful occupation of Corsica, Hood, ever the strategist, issued orders for Nelson to initiate diplomatic relations with the city-state of [Genoa], a strategically vital potential ally in the ongoing conflict. Soon after, Hood himself returned to England, his command in the Mediterranean passing to Admiral [William Hotham, 1st Baron Hotham]. Nelson, seizing a moment of respite, put into Leghorn. While the Agamemnon underwent necessary repairs, he met with other naval officers at the port and, ever the romantic, indulged in a brief affair with a local woman named Adelaide Correglia. Hotham, with the remainder of the fleet, arrived in December, whereupon Nelson and the Agamemnon embarked on a series of cruises with them throughout late 1794 and early 1795. On 8 March, intelligence reached Hotham regarding the French fleet, reportedly at sea and steering a course for Corsica. He immediately set out to intercept them, and Nelson, with palpable excitement, eagerly anticipated his first true fleet action. The French, however, proved reluctant to engage, and for much of 12 March, the two fleets merely shadowed each other. The following day, a stroke of good fortune for the British, two of the French ships collided, presenting Nelson with a golden opportunity to engage the significantly larger 84-gun *Ça Ira*. This engagement, a testament to Nelson's aggressive tactics, persisted for two and a half hours, with Nelson inflicting heavy casualties and considerable damage. However, the timely arrival of two more French ships forced Nelson to tactically veer away.

The fleets, like two wary predators, continued their shadowing dance, before making contact once more on 14 March at the [Battle of Genoa]. Nelson, with characteristic zeal, joined the other British ships in a concentrated assault on the already battered *Ça Ira*, which was now under tow from the *Censeur*. Heavily damaged and utterly outmatched, the two French ships were compelled to surrender, and Nelson, ever the victor, took possession of the *Censeur*. Defeated at sea, the French, their grand designs for invading Corsica utterly thwarted, abandoned their plans and retreated ignominiously to port.

### Skirmishes and the retreat from Italy

Nelson and the fleet maintained their presence in the Mediterranean throughout the summer of 1795. On 4 July, the Agamemnon departed from San Fiorenzo with a modest force of frigates and sloops, bound for Genoa. On 6 July, Nelson, with an almost uncanny knack for finding trouble, unexpectedly encountered the French fleet and found himself relentlessly pursued by several, significantly larger, ships-of-the-line. He executed a tactical retreat to San Fiorenzo, arriving just ahead of the pursuing French, who, alerted by Nelson's signal guns, broke off their chase as the British fleet in the harbour became aware of their presence. Hotham, with characteristic indecision, pursued the French to the [Hyères Islands], but ultimately failed to bring them to a decisive action. [Several small engagements were fought](/Naval_Battle_of_Hy%C3%A8res_Islands), but to Nelson's palpable dismay, he saw little direct action. Nelson subsequently returned to operate out of Genoa, diligently intercepting and inspecting merchantmen, and, with his usual audacity, cutting out suspicious vessels from both enemy and neutral harbours. Nelson, ever the strategist, formulated ambitious plans for amphibious landings and naval assaults, aimed at frustrating the relentless advance of the [French Army of Italy], which was now bearing down on Genoa. However, he found little enthusiasm for his bold schemes from Hotham, who remained, predictably, cautious. In November, Hotham was replaced by [Sir Hyde Parker (admiral)], but the strategic situation in Italy was rapidly deteriorating for the British: the French were conducting increasingly aggressive raids around Genoa, and strong [Jacobin (politics)] sentiment was rife within the city itself.

A large-scale French assault at the end of November shattered the allied lines, forcing a general, and rather undignified, retreat towards Genoa. Nelson's forces, with their customary efficiency, were able to provide crucial cover for the withdrawing army, preventing them from being surrounded and utterly annihilated. However, he commanded too few ships and soldiers to materially alter the grim strategic situation. The British, faced with an untenable position, were compelled to withdraw from the Italian ports. Nelson returned to Corsica on 30 November, seething with anger and consumed by depression over the British failure, and, for a rare moment, questioning his own future within the navy.

### Jervis and the evacuation of the Mediterranean

In January 1796, a new figure arrived to take command-in-chief of the fleet in the Mediterranean: [Sir John Jervis, 1st Earl of St Vincent]. A man of decisive action, Jervis, recognising Nelson's unique talents, promptly appointed him to exercise independent command over the ships tasked with blockading the French coast, elevating him to the rank of [commodore (Royal Navy)]. Nelson spent the first half of the year tirelessly conducting operations aimed at frustrating French advances and bolstering Britain's increasingly beleaguered Italian allies. Despite achieving minor successes in intercepting small French warships—such as in the [action of 31 May 1796], where Nelson's squadron managed to capture a convoy of seven small vessels—he began to harbour a growing conviction that the British presence on the Italian peninsula was becoming, quite simply, futile. In June, the Agamemnon, a ship that had served him well, was dispatched to Britain for much-needed repairs, and Nelson was transferred to the formidable 74-gun HMS&#160; Captain.

The very same month, the French forces, with relentless momentum, thrust towards Leghorn, their capture of the city appearing all but inevitable. Nelson, with characteristic urgency, hurried there to oversee the critical evacuation of British nationals, transporting them to the relative safety of Corsica. Following this, Jervis issued orders for him to blockade the newly captured French port. In July, he oversaw the occupation of [Elba], a small victory in a sea of setbacks. However, by September, the Genoese, with a predictable lack of conviction, had broken their neutrality to openly declare in favour of the French. By October, the precarious Genoese position, coupled with the relentless French advances, led the British high command to the grim conclusion that the Mediterranean fleet could no longer be adequately supplied. The order was given: the fleet was to be evacuated to Gibraltar. Nelson, ever the man for a crisis, helped oversee the withdrawal from Corsica, and by December 1796, found himself aboard the frigate HMS Minerve, diligently covering the evacuation of the garrison at Elba. He then set sail for Gibraltar, a retreat that must have chafed at his restless spirit.

During the passage, Nelson, with a burst of his old audacity, [captured the Spanish frigate](/Action_of_19_December_1796) *Santa Sabina*. He promptly placed Lieutenants Jonathan Culverhouse and [Sir Thomas Hardy, 1st Baronet] in charge of the captured vessel, taking the frigate's Spanish captain on board the Minerve. However, the *Santa Sabina* was merely a part of a much larger Spanish force, and the very next morning, two formidable Spanish ships-of-the-line and a frigate were sighted, closing fast. Unable to outrun them, Nelson, with a characteristic flash of defiance, was initially determined to fight. But Culverhouse and Hardy, displaying quick thinking, raised the British colours and bravely sailed northeast, deliberately drawing the Spanish ships after them until they were inevitably captured. This selfless act provided Nelson with the crucial opportunity to escape. Nelson continued on, eventually rendezvousing with the British fleet at Elba, where he spent a rather tense Christmas. He then set sail for Gibraltar in late January. Upon learning that the Spanish fleet had departed from [Cartagena, Spain], he paused just long enough to collect Hardy, Culverhouse, and the rest of the prize crew captured with the *Santa Sabina*, before pressing on through the straits to join Jervis off [Cadiz].

## Battle of Cape St Vincent

•
Main article: [Battle of Cape St Vincent (1797)](/Battle_of_Cape_St_Vincent_(1797))

Nelson receives the surrender of the San Nicholas , an 1806 portrait by [Richard Westall](/Richard_Westall)

Nelson, with his usual flair for dramatic timing, rejoined Sir John Jervis' fleet off [Cape St Vincent], promptly reporting the movements of the Spanish. Jervis, a man of action, decided to engage, and the two formidable fleets clashed on 14 February 1797. Nelson, finding himself somewhat inconveniently positioned towards the rear of the British line, quickly realised it would be an unacceptably long time before he could bring the Captain into the heart of the action. With a calculated defiance that would become his hallmark, Nelson deliberately disobeyed direct orders and [wore ship], breaking from the rigid line and boldly heading to engage the Spanish vanguard. His targets: the immense 112-gun *San Josef*, the formidable 80-gun *San Nicolas*, and the colossal 130-gun *Santísima Trinidad*. The Captain, with Nelson at its helm, engaged all three, albeit with the timely assistance of HMS&#160; Culloden, which had, rather commendably, come to Nelson's aid. After an hour of relentless broadsides that left both the Captain and Culloden badly damaged, Nelson found his ship miraculously alongside the *San Nicolas*. With a rallying cry of "Westminster Abbey or glorious victory!", he personally led a boarding party across, forcing her to surrender. The *San Josef*, attempting to come to the aid of her compatriot, became entangled with her, rendering her immobile. Nelson, with an almost theatrical flourish, led his boarding party directly from the deck of the *San Nicolas* onto the *San Josef*, capturing her as well. As night descended, the Spanish fleet, broken and demoralised, disengaged and fled towards Cadiz. Four ships had surrendered to the British, and a remarkable two of them bore the distinct mark of Nelson's audacious hand. It was, quite astonishingly, the first time in three centuries that a British flag officer had personally led a boarding party.

Nelson, for all his undeniable victory, had, quite explicitly, disobeyed direct orders. Jervis, a shrewd judge of character and perhaps secretly impressed by the sheer audacity, chose not to officially reprimand him, a decision that speaks volumes. However, he conspicuously omitted any mention of Nelson's insubordinate, albeit brilliant, actions in his official report of the battle. He did, however, pen a private letter to the [First Lord of the Admiralty], [George Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer], in which he conceded that Nelson had "contributed very much to the fortune of the day." Nelson, never one to shy away from self-promotion, also wrote several letters detailing his victory, proudly noting that his audacious manoeuvre was being referred to amongst the fleet as "Nelson's Patent Bridge for boarding first rates." Nelson's account was later challenged by Rear Admiral [Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet, of Harburn], who had been aboard HMS&#160; Prince George. Parker contended that Nelson had been supported by several more ships than he acknowledged, and furthermore, that the *San Josef* had already [struck her colours] by the time Nelson boarded her. Despite these dissenting voices, Nelson's version of his pivotal role largely prevailed, and the victory was rapturously received in Britain. Jervis, as a direct consequence, was elevated to [Earl St Vincent], and on 17 May, Nelson himself was knighted, becoming a [Knight of the Bath]. On 20 February, in a standard promotion based purely on seniority and entirely unrelated to his heroic actions in battle, Nelson was promoted to [Rear Admiral of the Blue].

## Admiral, 1797–1801

### Action off Cadiz

•
Main article: [Assault on Cádiz](/Assault_on_C%C3%A1diz)

Nelson was assigned HMS&#160; Theseus as his new [flagship] and, on 27 May 1797, received orders to station himself off Cadiz. His mission was twofold: to diligently monitor the Spanish fleet and to eagerly await the anticipated arrival of Spanish treasure ships from the American colonies. Ever the direct leader, he personally led an amphibious assault on 3 July. During this intense action, Nelson's barge, in a rather dramatic turn of events, collided with that of the Spanish commander. A fierce hand-to-hand struggle erupted between the two crews. Nelson himself was almost cut down twice, his life saved both times by a quick-thinking sailor named John Sykes, who bravely took the blows himself and was severely wounded. The British raiding force ultimately captured the Spanish boat and triumphantly towed her back to the Theseus. It was during this period that Nelson, with his characteristic strategic ambition, developed an audacious scheme to capture [Santa Cruz de Tenerife], specifically targeting a large quantity of [specie] from the treasure ship *Principe de Asturias*, which was reported to have recently arrived in port.

### Battle of Santa Cruz de Tenerife

•
Main article: [Battle of Santa Cruz de Tenerife (1797)](/Battle_of_Santa_Cruz_de_Tenerife_(1797))

Nelson wounded during the Battle of Santa Cruz de Tenerife; 1806 painting by [Richard Westall](/Richard_Westall)

The battle plan, conceived with Nelson's typical blend of audacity and aggression, called for a combined assault involving naval bombardments and a decisive amphibious landing. The initial attempt, however, was abruptly called off after unforeseen adverse currents hampered the landing parties, costing the British the crucial element of surprise. Nelson, undeterred, immediately ordered another assault, but this too was fiercely beaten back. He then meticulously prepared for a third attempt, scheduled to take place under the cover of night. Although he personally led one of the battalions, the operation ultimately ended in a dismal failure. The Spanish defenders, it turned out, were far better prepared than anticipated and had secured formidable defensive positions. Several of the British boats, in the chaos and confusion of the night, failed to land at their designated points, while those that did were met with a devastating hail of gunfire and [grapeshot]. Nelson's own boat, against the odds, reached its intended landing point, but as he stepped ashore, he was struck in the right arm by a musketball, which fractured his [humerus] in multiple places. He was swiftly rowed back to the Theseus to be attended to by its surgeon, Thomas Eshelby. Upon his arrival at the ship, in a display of characteristic stoicism and a touch of grim humour, he famously refused assistance, declaring:

"Let me alone! I have yet legs left and one arm. Tell the surgeon to make haste and get his instruments. I know I must lose my right arm and the sooner it is off, the better".

A hastily applied tourniquet saved him from [exsanguinating], and Eshelby, with grim efficiency, amputated the majority of his right arm. Within a remarkable half-hour, Nelson, his body mangled but his mind still sharp, had returned to issuing orders to his captains. Years later, he would, with a dry wit, excuse himself to Commodore [John Thomas Duckworth] for his inability to write longer letters, claiming he was not naturally left-handed. He later reported experiencing the chilling sensation of a [phantom limb] in the area of his amputation, a phenomenon that led him to declare he had "found the direct evidence of the existence of soul." Meanwhile, a force under [Sir Thomas Troubridge, 1st Baronet] had, against heavy odds, fought their way to the main square but could advance no further. Unable to return to the fleet due to their boats having been sunk, Troubridge was compelled to enter into negotiations with the Spanish commander, resulting in the British being permitted to withdraw. The expedition, a costly and humiliating affair, failed to achieve any of its objectives and left a quarter of the landing force either dead or wounded. The squadron lingered off Tenerife for a further three days, and by 16 August, had rejoined Lord John Jervis' fleet off Cadiz. Despondent, Nelson, in a rare moment of vulnerability, penned a letter to Jervis:

"A left-handed Admiral will never again be considered as useful, therefore the sooner I get to a very humble cottage the better, and make room for a better man to serve the state".

The severity of his post-operative pain necessitated Nelson's return to England, accompanied by Thomas Eshelby. He made the journey aboard HMS Seahorse, arriving at [Spithead] on 1 September. He was, to his probable surprise, met with a hero's welcome; the British public, having lionised Nelson after Cape St Vincent, now offered him their profound sympathy for his wound. They, in their collective wisdom, refused to attribute the defeat at Tenerife to him, preferring instead to lay blame on the perceived poor planning of St Vincent, the [Secretary at War], [William Windham], or even the Prime Minister, [William Pitt the Younger]. Such is the fickle nature of public opinion.

### Return to England

Nelson, wounded and weary, returned to Bath with Fanny, before relocating to London in October 1797 to seek expert medical attention for his amputation wound. While in the capital, news reached him of [Admiral Duncan, 1st Viscount Duncan of Camperdown]'s decisive victory over the [Batavian Republic] fleet at the [Battle of Camperdown]. Nelson, with a characteristic blend of competitive spirit and perhaps a touch of morbid humour, famously exclaimed that he would have gladly given his other arm to have been present at that triumph. He spent the concluding months of 1797 recuperating in London, a period during which he was awarded the prestigious [Freedom of the City of London] and a generous pension of £1,000 (equivalent to £130,800&#32;in 2023) per annum. He invested this money in purchasing Round Wood Farm near [Ipswich], harbouring the intention of retiring there with Fanny. Despite these carefully laid plans, Nelson, in a twist of fate, would never actually reside there.

Although surgeons were initially unable to remove the central [ligature (medicine)] from his amputation site, which had caused considerable inflammation and infection, it eventually came out of its own accord in early December, leading to a rapid improvement in Nelson's condition. Eager to return to the sea, his natural habitat, he began to vigorously agitate for a new command. He was initially promised the formidable 80-gun HMS&#160; Foudroyant. However, as she was not yet ready for service, Nelson was instead given command of the 74-gun HMS&#160; Vanguard, and he promptly appointed [Sir Edward Berry, 1st Baronet] as his [flag captain]. French activities in the Mediterranean theatre were, once again, raising considerable concern within the Admiralty, as [Napoleon] was observed gathering substantial forces in Southern France, but the ultimate destination of his army remained a closely guarded secret. Nelson and the Vanguard were consequently dispatched to Cadiz to reinforce the fleet. On 28 March 1798, Nelson hoisted his flag and set sail to join Earl St Vincent. St Vincent, in turn, sent him on to Toulon with a small force to reconnoitre French activities.

### Hunting the French

•
Main article: [Mediterranean campaign of 1798](/Mediterranean_campaign_of_1798)

Nelson, ever the hunter, passed through the [Strait of Gibraltar] and took up position off Toulon by 17 May. However, his squadron was unexpectedly dispersed and blown southwards by a powerful gale that swept through the area on 20 May. While the British were battling the relentless storm, Napoleon, ever the opportunist, set sail with his massive invasion fleet, commanded by [Vice Admiral] [François-Paul Brueys d'Aigalliers]. Nelson, now reinforced with a number of additional ships from St Vincent, immediately set off in hot pursuit. Nelson began a systematic search of the Italian coast for Napoleon's elusive fleet, but his efforts were hampered by a critical lack of frigates, vessels essential for acting as fast scouts. Napoleon, in the meantime, had already arrived at [Malta] and, after a formidable show of force, secured the island's surrender. Nelson followed him there, but by the time he arrived, the French had, with an irritating precision, already departed. After a swift conference with his captains, he concluded that Napoleon's most probable destination was now Egypt, and accordingly, set a course for [Alexandria]. However, upon Nelson's arrival on 28 June, he found no sign of the French. Dismayed, he withdrew and began searching to the east of the port, a rather frustrating game of cat and mouse. During this period, Napoleon's fleet, with infuriating timing, arrived in Alexandria on 1 July and landed their forces unopposed. Brueys, meanwhile, anchored his fleet in [Aboukir Bay], positioning it to provide support to Napoleon should the need arise.

Meanwhile, Nelson, in a display of almost superhuman persistence, had once again traversed the Mediterranean in a fruitless attempt to locate the French, eventually returning to Naples to re-provision. When he again set sail, his initial intention was to search the seas off [Cyprus], but he made a last-minute decision to pass Alexandria once more for a final, desperate check. Along the way, his force serendipitously encountered and captured a French merchant ship. This vessel, a stroke of pure luck, provided the first concrete news of the French fleet: they had passed south-east of [Crete] a month prior, undeniably heading towards Alexandria. Nelson, with renewed urgency, hurried to the port, but again found it empty of the French. Searching relentlessly along the coast, he finally, gloriously, discovered the French fleet at anchor in Aboukir Bay on 1 August 1798. The hunt was over.

### Battle of the Nile

•
Main article: [Battle of the Nile](/Battle_of_the_Nile)

[Battle of the Nile](/Battle_of_the_Nile), 1 August 1798 at 10&#160;pm , painting by [Thomas Luny](/Thomas_Luny)

Nelson, with an almost preternatural calm, immediately began to prepare for battle, reiterating a sentiment he had famously expressed at the Battle of Cape St Vincent: "Before this time tomorrow, I shall have gained a peerage or Westminster Abbey." It was late by the time the British fleet arrived, and the French, anchored in a seemingly impregnable position and possessing a combined firepower superior to Nelson's fleet, did not, in their arrogance, anticipate an immediate attack. However, Nelson, ever the iconoclast, immediately ordered his ships to advance. The French line was anchored perilously close to a line of [shoals], a position they mistakenly believed would secure their [port (nautical)] side from any assault; Brueys had, quite conventionally, assumed the British would adhere to traditional tactics and attack his centre from the [starboard] side. However, [Captain Thomas Foley (Royal Navy officer)], aboard HMS&#160; Goliath, discovered a critical, unseen gap between the shoals and the French ships, and, with audacious initiative, steered the Goliath directly into this channel. The utterly unprepared French found themselves attacked on both sides; the British fleet, executing Nelson's unconventional plan, split, with some vessels following Foley and others passing down the starboard side of the French line.

The British fleet was soon heavily engaged, systematically passing down the French line and engaging their ships one by one. Nelson, on the Vanguard, personally engaged the *Spartiate*, while simultaneously coming under fire from the *Aquilon*. At approximately eight o'clock, he was on the quarterdeck with Edward Berry when a piece of French shot struck him squarely in the forehead. He fell to the deck, a flap of torn skin obscuring his remaining good eye. Blinded and half-stunned, he was convinced he was dying and cried out, "I am killed. Remember me to my wife." He was swiftly carried below to be attended to by the surgeon. After a rapid examination, the surgeon pronounced the wound non-threatening and applied a temporary bandage. The French van, pounded relentlessly by British fire from both sides, had begun to surrender, and the victorious British ships continued their relentless advance down the line, bringing Brueys' immense 118-gun flagship, the *Orient*, under constant, heavy fire. The *Orient* inevitably caught fire under this devastating bombardment and later exploded in a spectacular, cataclysmic display. Nelson, ever the commander, briefly returned to the deck to direct the ongoing battle, but retreated back to the surgeon after witnessing the utter destruction of the *Orient*.

The Battle of the Nile delivered a crushing blow to Napoleon's grand ambitions in the east. His fleet was, quite simply, annihilated; the *Orient*, another ship, and two frigates were utterly consumed by fire, while seven 74-gun ships and two 80-gun ships were captured. Only two ships-of-the-line and two frigates managed to escape the carnage. The forces Napoleon had so painstakingly brought to Egypt were now hopelessly stranded. Napoleon, ever the pragmatist, subsequently launched an attack north along the Mediterranean coast, but his army was ultimately defeated by Turkish defenders, ably supported by Captain Sir [Sidney Smith (admiral)], at the [Siege of Acre (1799)]. Napoleon, abandoning his army to its fate, then covertly sailed back to France, miraculously evading detection by British ships. Given its profound strategic importance, historians such as [Ernle Bradford] regard Nelson's achievement at the Nile as the most significant of his entire career, even surpassing the legendary triumph at Trafalgar seven years later. A rather bold claim, but one with considerable merit.

### Rewards

[Lady Hamilton](/Emma,_Lady_Hamilton) as either a [bacchante](/Maenad) or [Ariadne](/Ariadne) by [Élisabeth Louise Vigée Le Brun](/%C3%89lisabeth_Louise_Vig%C3%A9e_Le_Brun), c. &#8201;1790; a painting owned by Nelson which hung above his bed until his death

Nelson, ever the meticulous communicator, drafted dispatches for the Admiralty and oversaw the necessary temporary repairs to the Vanguard before setting sail for Naples, where he was met with a predictably enthusiastic, almost hysterical, celebration. [King Ferdinand IV of Naples], accompanied by the Hamiltons, a trio now inextricably linked, personally greeted him upon his arrival at port, and [Sir William Hamilton (diplomat)] extended an invitation for Nelson to stay at his home. Celebrations, naturally, were held in honour of Nelson's birthday in September 1798, and he attended a lavish banquet at the Hamiltons' residence, where other officers had, with a keen eye for social intrigue, begun to notice his rather undeniable attentions to [Emma, Lady Hamilton].

Lord Jervis himself had, by this point, begun to express concern regarding reports of Nelson's increasingly unconventional behaviour, but in early October, news of Nelson's monumental victory at the Nile finally reached London, completely overshadowing any burgeoning scandal. The [First Lord of the Admiralty], [George Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer], upon hearing the news, reportedly fainted. Celebrations erupted across the entire country; balls and victory feasts were held with extravagant abandon, and church bells pealed in joyous cacophony. The City of London awarded Nelson and his captains ceremonial swords, while the King, in a gesture of royal approval, ordered that they be presented with special medals. Emperor [Paul I of Russia] sent Nelson a lavish gift, and [Sultan] [Selim III] of the [Ottoman Empire] bestowed upon Nelson the prestigious [Order of the Turkish Crescent], along with the exquisite diamond [chelengk] from his own turban, a truly extraordinary honour, in recognition of Nelson's pivotal role in restoring Ottoman rule to Egypt.

[Samuel Hood, 1st Viscount Hood], after a conversation with the [Prime Minister William Pitt the Younger], rather confidently informed Nelson's wife Fanny that her husband would likely be granted a [viscountcy], a similar honour to Jervis' [earldom] after [Cape St Vincent] and [Adam Duncan, 1st Viscount Duncan]'s viscountcy after Camperdown. However, Lord Spencer, perhaps driven by a desire to maintain a rigid hierarchy or simply a latent sense of propriety, demurred, arguing that such an elevated award would establish an unwelcome precedent, as Nelson was merely in detached command of a squadron, rather than being the commander-in-chief of the entire fleet. Consequently, Nelson received the somewhat lesser, but still significant, title of [Baron Nelson] of the Nile.

### Neapolitan campaign

Castello di Maniace , [caput](/Caput) of the [Dukedom of Bronte](/Dukedom_of_Bronte), situated 5 miles north of the town of Bronte. Painted in 1876 by [Sir John Walrond, 1st Baronet](/Sir_John_Walrond,_1st_Baronet)

Nelson, with a characteristic blend of ambition and vanity, was profoundly dismayed by the decision of [George Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer], declaring, with a flourish, that he would rather have received no title at all than a mere [barony]. However, his spirits were considerably buoyed by the effusive attention showered upon him by the citizens of Naples, the undeniable prestige accorded to him by the kingdom's elite, and, perhaps most significantly, the abundant comforts he received at the Hamilton residence. He became a frequent visitor, attending numerous functions held in his honour, or embarking on leisurely tours of nearby attractions with Emma, who was now almost constantly at his side and with whom he had, quite undeniably, fallen deeply in love. Orders eventually arrived from the Admiralty, instructing him to blockade the French forces entrenched in Alexandria and Malta, a task Nelson, with a clear preference for more engaging pursuits, delegated to his capable captains [Sir Samuel Hood, 1st Baronet] and [Alexander Ball]. Despite ostensibly enjoying his rather decadent lifestyle in Naples, even while judging it, with a characteristically cynical assessment, to be a "country of fiddlers and poets, whores and scoundrels," which he found "less than desirable," Nelson began to entertain thoughts of returning to England. However, King [Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies] had, by this point, faced an extended period of intense pressure from his formidable wife, [Maria Carolina of Austria], who was vehemently advocating for an aggressive foreign policy towards France—a country that had, five years prior, brutally beheaded her sister, Queen [Marie Antoinette]. Sir [William Hamilton (diplomat)], aligning himself with Queen Maria Carolina's fervent anti-French sentiment, joined in agreement, and the King, after much deliberation, finally consented to declare war on France.

The [Neapolitan Army (Napoleonic)], under the command of Austrian General [Karl Mack von Leiberich] and bolstered by the strategic support of Nelson's fleet, successfully retook Rome from the French in late November 1798. However, the French forces, with their usual resilience, regrouped outside Rome and, after receiving substantial reinforcements, decisively routed the Neapolitans. In utter disarray, the Neapolitan army fled back to Naples, with the relentlessly pursuing French close behind. Nelson, ever the pragmatist in a crisis, hastily organised the critical evacuation of the Royal Family, several prominent nobles, and British nationals, including the Hamiltons. The evacuation commenced on 23 December and navigated through heavy gales before reaching the relative safety of [Palermo] on 26 December. With the abrupt departure of the Royal Family, Naples descended into predictable anarchy, and news reached Palermo in January of the French, under General [Jean Étienne Championnet], entering the city and proclaiming the short-lived [Parthenopaean Republic]. Nelson was promoted to [Rear-Admiral of the Red] on 14 February 1799, and for several months, found himself engaged in the rather tedious task of blockading Naples, while a burgeoning popular counter-revolutionary force under [Cardinal Ruffo], known as the Sanfedisti, marched with grim determination to retake the city. In late June, Ruffo's army, with a brutal efficiency, entered Naples, forcing the French and their local supporters to withdraw to the city's fortifications, as predictable rioting and opportunistic looting erupted amongst the ill-disciplined Neapolitan troops.

Dismayed by the escalating bloodshed, Ruffo, seeking a pragmatic resolution, agreed to a [capitulation (surrender)] with the Jacobin forces, a treaty that guaranteed them safe conduct to France. Nelson, however, arrived off Naples on 24 June to find this treaty already in effect. His subsequent role in what unfolded remains, to this day, a subject of considerable controversy. Nelson, aboard the Foudroyant, was predictably outraged. Backed by King Ferdinand IV, he vehemently insisted that the rebels must surrender unconditionally. They, quite understandably, refused. Nelson, in a move that has puzzled historians ever since, appears to have momentarily relented, and the Jacobin forces began to march out to the awaiting transports. Then, with a sudden and chilling reversal, Nelson had the transports seized. He took those who had surrendered under the terms of the treaty under armed guard, including the former Admiral [Francesco Caracciolo (naval officer)]. Nelson, with a cold efficiency, ordered Caracciolo's trial by [court-martial] and, crucially, refused Caracciolo's request for its conduct by British officers. Caracciolo was also denied the fundamental right to summon witnesses in his defence and was instead tried by royalist Neapolitan officers, a clear miscarriage of justice. He was, predictably, sentenced to death. Caracciolo requested to be shot rather than hanged, a more honourable death, but Nelson, seemingly following the wishes of Queen Maria Carolina, a close friend of [Lady Hamilton], denied this request as well. He even ignored the court's own plea to allow 24 hours for Caracciolo to prepare himself. Caracciolo was hanged aboard the Neapolitan frigate Minerva at 5 o'clock that very same afternoon.

Nelson, displaying a chilling detachment, kept most of the Jacobins imprisoned on the transports and began the systematic process of handing hundreds over for trial and summary execution. He steadfastly refused to intervene, despite fervent pleas for [clemency] from both the Hamiltons and even Queen Maria Carolina herself. When the transports were finally permitted to carry the surviving Jacobins to France, less than one-third were still alive. On 13 August 1799, in a rather grand gesture of reward for his unwavering support of the monarchy, King Ferdinand IV bestowed upon Nelson the newly created title of [Duke of Bronte] in the peerage of the [Kingdom of Sicily] as his perpetual property, along with the extensive estate of the former [Benedictine abbey] of Santa Maria di Maniace—which he later, rather fittingly, transformed into the [Castello di Nelson]—situated between the [comunes] of [Bronte, Sicily] and [Maniace], subsequently known as the Duchy of Nelson. In 1799, in a rare display of humanitarian intervention, Nelson actively opposed the mistreatment of slaves held in Portuguese galleys off Palermo and intervened directly to secure their release. Nelson personally petitioned the Portuguese commander, Marquiz de Niza, to hand over the slaves. The marquis, perhaps surprisingly, acquiesced to this unusual request, allowing 24 slaves to be transferred to HMS&#160; Bonne Citoyenne. Their blessings to Nelson, a chorus of gratitude, rang out across the harbour as their names were added to the sloop's already crowded muster book.

### The Battle of the Malta convoy

#### Siege of Malta

•
Further information: [Siege of Malta (1798–1800)](/Siege_of_Malta_(1798%E2%80%931800))

Nelson returned to Palermo in August, and in September, found himself the senior officer in the Mediterranean after Lord John Jervis' successor, [George Elphinstone, 1st Viscount Keith], had departed to chase the French and Spanish fleets into the Atlantic. Nelson spent the majority of 1799 ensconced at the Neapolitan court, a rather comfortable, if strategically uninspiring, posting. However, he put to sea once more in February 1800 after Lord Keith's return. Keith, ever the stickler for orders, instructed Nelson to assist in the [siege of Malta], where the [Royal Navy] was maintaining a tight blockade. On 18 February, the *Généreux*—a survivor, remarkably, of the Battle of the Nile—was sighted, and Nelson, with his characteristic zeal, gave chase, capturing her after [a short battle](/Battle_of_the_Malta_Convoy_(1800)) and, crucially, winning Keith's approval. Nelson and the Hamiltons, a rather unconventional trio, sailed aboard the Foudroyant from Naples on a brief cruise around [Malta] in April 1800 and anchored at [Marsaxlokk]. Here, Nelson and Emma lived together openly, hosted by [Sir Thomas Troubridge, 1st Baronet] and [Thomas Graham, 1st Baron Lynedoch]. It was during this period that Nelson and Lady Emma Hamilton's illegitimate daughter, [Horatia Nelson], was most likely conceived.

Nelson, it must be noted, cultivated a rather difficult relationship with his superior officer, Lord Keith. He was, by this point, acquiring a distinct reputation for insubordination, having, on more than one occasion, initially refused to dispatch ships when Keith requested them, and at times, returning to Palermo without explicit orders, citing dubious claims of poor health. Keith's reports, coupled with the increasingly persistent rumours concerning Nelson's undeniably close relationship with Emma Hamilton, were now circulating with alarming speed around London. Lord Spencer, with a pointed lack of subtlety, penned a letter strongly suggesting Nelson return home.

### Return to England

[Emma Hamilton](/Emma,_Lady_Hamilton) in an 1800 portrait owned by Nelson
An antique photograph of a portrait of [Horatia Ward](/Horatia_Nelson) (née Nelson)

The recall of Sir William Hamilton to Britain provided a rather convenient impetus for Nelson's own return. In June, Nelson departed Malta and, with a certain irony given his personal entanglements, conveyed Queen [Maria Carolina of Austria] and her rather extensive suite to [Leghorn (city)]. Upon his arrival, Nelson, in a move that further highlighted his defiance of authority, shifted his flag to HMS&#160; Alexander, but again openly disobeyed Lord Keith's orders by flatly refusing to join the main fleet. Keith, a man not to be trifled with, travelled directly to Leghorn to demand an explanation in person, and steadfastly refused to be swayed by the Queen's pleas to allow her to be conveyed in a British ship. Faced with Keith's unyielding demands, Nelson, with visible reluctance, [struck his flag] and, bowing to Lady Hamilton's fervent wishes, opted to return to England over land. Nelson, the Hamiltons, and several other British travellers, a rather scandalous entourage, departed Leghorn for [Florence] on 13 July. Their journey took them through [Trieste] and [Vienna], where they spent three weeks, entertained lavishly by the local nobility and, rather remarkably, heard the [Missa in Angustiis] by [Joseph Haydn], a work now, rather fittingly, known as the "Nelson Mass." Haydn himself would meet them that August when they visited [Eisenstadt]. By September, they were in [Prague], and subsequently called at [Dresden], [Dessau] and [Hamburg]; from there, they caught a [packet boat] to [Great Yarmouth], finally arriving on 6 November. Nelson was, predictably, given a hero's welcome, and after being sworn in as a freeman of the borough, received the rapturous applause of the crowds. He then made his way to London, arriving on 9 November.

He attended court and was, as expected, the guest of honour at a seemingly endless series of banquets and balls. It was during this period that Fanny Nelson and Lady Emma Hamilton met for the first time, a rather awkward encounter one can only imagine. Nelson was reportedly cold and distant towards his wife, while his overt attentions to Lady Hamilton, and her increasingly noticeable obesity, became the avid subject of London gossip. With the marriage visibly disintegrating, Nelson began to harbour a profound aversion to even being in the same room as Fanny. Events reached their inevitable climax around Christmas, when, according to Nelson's solicitor, Fanny issued a stark ultimatum: he was to choose between her and Lady Hamilton. Nelson, with a rather predictable lack of decisiveness, replied that he loved Fanny but could not "forget his obligations" to Lady Hamilton. Nelson and Fanny never lived together again.

### The Baltic

Shortly after his arrival in England, Nelson, ever the man for a crisis, was appointed second-in-command of the [Channel Fleet] under Lord John Jervis. He was promoted to [Vice-Admiral of the Blue] on 1 January 1801, and travelled to [Plymouth], where he was granted the [freedom of the city] on 22 January. On 29 January 1801, Lady [Emma Hamilton] gave birth to their daughter, [Horatia Nelson]. Nelson was, by all accounts, delighted, but his joy was soon tempered by disappointment when he was instructed to move his flag from HMS&#160; San Josef to HMS&#160; St George, in preparation for a planned expedition to the Baltic. Tired of British ships imposing a relentless blockade against French trade and, more irritatingly, stopping and searching their merchantmen, the Russian, Prussian, Danish, and Swedish governments had formed an alliance, the Second League of Armed Neutrality, specifically to break this blockade. Nelson joined Admiral Sir [Hyde Parker (Royal Navy officer, born 1739)]'s fleet at Yarmouth, from where they set sail for the Danish coast in March. Upon their arrival, Parker was initially inclined to merely blockade Denmark and control the entrance to the Baltic, a cautious approach. But Nelson, ever the aggressor, vehemently urged a pre-emptive strike on the Danish fleet harboured in [Copenhagen]. He successfully convinced Parker to allow him to lead the assault and was given significant reinforcements. Parker himself would, with prudent caution, wait in the [Kattegat], covering Nelson's fleet in case of the arrival of the Swedish or Russian fleets.

### Battle of Copenhagen

•
Main article: [Battle of Copenhagen (1801)](/Battle_of_Copenhagen_(1801))

The Battle of Copenhagen, 2 April 1801 , by [Nicholas Pocock](/Nicholas_Pocock)
This glass was one of a set commissioned by Nelson to commemorate his victory at the Battle of Copenhagen.

On the crisp morning of 2 April 1801, Nelson began his audacious advance into Copenhagen harbour. The battle commenced rather inauspiciously for the British, with HMS Agamemnon, Bellona, and Russell all running aground, and the remainder of the fleet encountering far heavier fire from the Danish shore batteries than originally anticipated. Sir Hyde Parker, from his distant vantage point, dispatched the signal for Nelson to withdraw. Nelson, directing the chaotic action aboard HMS&#160; Elephant, was informed of this rather unwelcome signal by the signal lieutenant, Frederick Langford, but responded with a flash of characteristic anger: "I told you to look out on the Danish commodore and let me know when he surrendered. Keep your eyes fixed on him." He then, with a dramatic flourish, turned to his flag captain, [Thomas Foley (Royal Navy officer)], and declared, "You know, Foley, I have only one eye. I have a right to be blind sometimes." Raising the telescope to his blind eye, he added, "I really do not see the signal." A convenient blindness, indeed, and one that has since become the stuff of legend.

The battle raged for three brutal hours, leaving both the Danish and British fleets heavily damaged, a testament to the ferocity of the engagement. At length, Nelson, ever the pragmatist, dispatched a letter to the Danish commander, [Frederick VI of Denmark], calling for a truce, which the Prince, perhaps exhausted by the carnage, accepted. Parker, in a remarkable display of retrospective approval, endorsed Nelson's actions, and Nelson was granted the distinct honour of entering Copenhagen the following day to commence formal negotiations. At a banquet that very evening, he candidly informed Prince Frederick that the battle had been the most severe he had ever participated in. The outcome of the battle and the ensuing weeks of negotiations culminated in a 14-week armistice, with Nelson, a fitting reward for his audacity, becoming commander-in-chief in the [Baltic Sea] upon Parker's recall in May. As a further reward for his decisive victory, he was created [Viscount Nelson of the Nile] and of [Burnham Thorpe] in the County of Norfolk on 19 May 1801. Additionally, on 4 August 1801, he was created Baron Nelson of the Nile and of [Hilborough] in the County of Norfolk, with a special remainder ensuring the title could pass to his father and sisters. Nelson then sailed to the Russian naval base at [Tallinn] in May, where he received the welcome news that the pact of armed neutrality was to be disbanded. Satisfied with the expedition's successful outcome, he returned to England, arriving on 1 July.

## Leave in England, 1801–1803

In France, Napoleon, ever the architect of grand designs, was tirelessly amassing forces with the clear intention of [invading Great Britain]. After a brief, and no doubt eventful, spell in London, where he once again visited the Hamiltons, Nelson was, predictably, placed in charge of defending the [English Channel] to thwart this impending invasion. He spent the summer of 1801 [reconnoitering] the French coast, a period that saw little significant action apart from [a failed attack](/Raid_on_Boulogne_(1801)) on [Boulogne-sur-Mer] in August. On 1 October, the [Peace of Amiens] was signed between the British and the French, bringing a temporary, fragile cessation of hostilities. Nelson, his health once again failing, retired once more to Britain, choosing to reside with Sir William and Lady Hamilton. On 30 October, Nelson, ever keen to maintain his public profile, spoke in support of the [Henry Addington, 1st Viscount Sidmouth] government in the House of Lords, and subsequently made regular visits to attend parliamentary sessions.

### Grand tour

In the summer of 1802, Nelson and the Hamiltons, an increasingly notorious trio, embarked on a rather ambitious tour of England and Wales. Their itinerary was extensive, including stops at [Oxford], [Woodstock, Oxfordshire], [Blenheim Palace], [Gloucester], the [Forest of Dean], [Ross-on-Wye], then [Monmouth], [Abergavenny], [Brecon], [Carmarthen], [Milford Haven] (specifically the [New Inn, Pembrokeshire]), [Tenby] and [Swansea]. At [Merthyr Tydfil], he visited [Cyfarthfa Ironworks] to witness, firsthand, the place where the 104 guns for his flagship, HMS&#160; Victory, had been forged. The party then continued their journey, visiting [Nelson, Caerphilly], [Monmouth] (staying at the [Beaufort Arms Hotel, Monmouth]), [Hereford], [Ludlow], [Worcester, England], [Birmingham], [Warwick], [Althorp], before finally returning to [Merton Place] on 5 September, passing through countless other towns and villages along the way. Nelson, to his obvious satisfaction, found himself received as a hero almost everywhere he went (with the notable exception of Woodstock), and was the enthusiastic centre of numerous celebrations and events held in his honour. In September, Lady Hamilton, with characteristic extravagance, purchased Merton Place, a country estate in [Merton, London (parish)], [Surrey], where Nelson lived with the Hamiltons until William's death on 6 April 1803. The following month, war, with its grim predictability, erupted once again, and Nelson, his brief respite over, prepared to return to sea.

### Witness at the treason trial of Edward Despard

In January 1803, Nelson, in a rather unexpected turn, appeared as a [character witness] in the treason trial of his former comrade-in-arms, Colonel [Edward Despard]. Despard, by this point, was deeply entrenched in radical circles in London—a member of both the [London Corresponding Society] and the [Society of United Irishmen]—and was the alleged ringleader of a conspiracy to assassinate [King George III] and seize the [Tower of London] as part of the infamous [Despard Plot]. In court, Nelson, with a touch of nostalgia, recounted his shared service with Despard in the Caribbean during the American War. Under cross-examination, however, Nelson was forced to concede, rather awkwardly, that he had "lost sight of Despard for the last twenty years." Nelson, displaying a surprising degree of compassion, directed a further plea for clemency to Prime Minister [Henry Addington]. Addington later recounted to Nelson that "he and his family had sat up after supper, weeping over the letter." A rare glimpse into the emotional impact Nelson could wield, even in matters of state.

## Return to sea, 1803

•
Main article: [Trafalgar Campaign](/Trafalgar_Campaign)

Nelson was appointed commander-in-chief of the [Mediterranean Fleet] and, in a fitting tribute to his status, was given the [first-rate] HMS&#160; Victory as his flagship. He joined her at [Portsmouth], where he received orders to sail to Malta and assume command of a squadron there before joining the ongoing blockade of [Toulon]. Nelson arrived off Toulon in July 1803 and spent the subsequent year and a half diligently enforcing the blockade, a task that, while crucial, must have been utterly tedious for a man of his temperament. He was promoted to [Vice-Admiral of the White] while still at sea on 23 April 1804. In January 1805, the French fleet, under the command of Admiral [Pierre-Charles Villeneuve], managed to escape Toulon and, with infuriating skill, eluded the blockading British. Nelson immediately set off in pursuit, but after an exhaustive search of the eastern Mediterranean, he learned that the French had been blown back into Toulon. Villeneuve, with a remarkable talent for evasion, managed to break out a second time in April, and this time successfully passed through the Strait of Gibraltar and into the Atlantic—his destination, the West Indies.

Admiral Sir Robert Calder's action off Cape Finisterre, 23 July 1805 , by [William Anderson](/William_Anderson_(artist))

Nelson, with his customary relentless drive, gave chase, but spent the entire month of June in a fruitless search for the elusive fleet after arriving in the Caribbean. Villeneuve, exhibiting a bewildering lack of strategic purpose, briefly cruised around the islands before turning back towards Europe, acting in direct [contravention] of Napoleon's explicit orders. The returning French fleet was subsequently intercepted by a British fleet under [Sir Robert Calder] and engaged in the [Battle of Cape Finisterre (1805)], but, much to Nelson's probable exasperation, managed to reach [Ferrol, Spain] with only minor losses. Nelson returned to Gibraltar at the end of July and then travelled to England, dismayed by his persistent failure to bring the French to a decisive battle and fully expecting to be censured for it. To his utter surprise, he was instead given a rapturous reception from the vast crowds who had gathered to witness his arrival. Senior British officials, with a keen eye for public sentiment, congratulated him for sustaining the close pursuit, crediting him with single-handedly saving the West Indies from a French invasion. Nelson briefly stayed in London, where he was cheered wherever he went, before visiting Merton Place to see Lady Hamilton, arriving in late August. He entertained a number of his friends and relations there over the coming month, and, ever the strategist, began meticulously planning for a grand engagement with the enemy fleet, one that would, he hoped, surprise his foes by forcing a [pell-mell] battle upon them.

Captain [Henry Blackwood] arrived at Merton early on 2 September, bringing the crucial news that the French and Spanish fleets had combined and were currently at anchor in Cádiz. Nelson, with characteristic urgency, hurried to London, where he met with cabinet ministers and was, without hesitation, given command of the fleet tasked with blockading Cádiz. While awaiting one of these critical meetings on 24 September with [Robert Stewart, Viscount Castlereagh], the [Secretary of State for War and the Colonies], Nelson and Major General [Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington]—the future [Duke of Wellington (title)]—met briefly in a waiting area. Wellington was there to be debriefed on his Indian operations, and Nelson on his recent chase and future plans. Wellington later recalled, with a distinct lack of admiration, "[Nelson] entered at once into conversation with me, if I can call it conversation, for it was almost all on his side and all about himself and, in reality, a style so vain and so silly as to surprise and almost disgust me." After a few minutes, Nelson, perhaps sensing the awkwardness, left the room. However, upon being informed who his companion truly was, he promptly returned and initiated a far more earnest and intelligent discussion with the young Wellesley. This second conversation, lasting a quarter of an hour, encompassed topics such as the ongoing war, the precarious state of the colonies, and the complex geopolitical situation. On this second interaction, Wellington, remarkably, recalled, "I don't know I ever had a conversation that interested me more." This brief, and rather telling, encounter was the only meeting between the two towering figures of British military history.

Nelson returned briefly to Merton to meticulously set his affairs in order and bid a poignant farewell to Emma before travelling back to London and then on to Portsmouth, arriving there early on the morning of 14 September. He breakfasted at the George Inn with his friends [George Rose (Treasurer of the Navy)], the [Vice-President of the Board of Trade], and [George Canning], the [Treasurer of the Navy]. Word of Nelson's presence at the inn spread rapidly, and a large crowd of well-wishers quickly gathered. They accompanied Nelson to his barge and cheered him off, a gesture Nelson acknowledged by graciously raising his hat. He was recorded as having turned to his colleague and stated, with a characteristic blend of humility and pride: "I had their huzzas before; I have their hearts now." The [Romantic literature in English] poet [Robert Southey] later reported on the emotional scene, noting: "Many were in tears and many knelt down before him and blessed him as he passed."

Victory joined the British fleet off Cádiz on 27 September, and Nelson, with his usual decisive manner, took over command from Vice Admiral [Cuthbert Collingwood, 1st Baron Collingwood]. Nelson spent the subsequent weeks meticulously preparing and refining his tactical plans for the anticipated battle, and diligently dining with his captains to ensure they fully understood his intentions. He devised a revolutionary plan of attack, one that boldly anticipated the allied fleet would form up in a traditional [line of battle]. Drawing on his own hard-won experience from the Nile and Copenhagen, and the successful examples of [Adam Duncan, 1st Viscount Duncan] at [Camperdown] and [George Brydges Rodney, 1st Baron Rodney] at the [Battle of the Saintes], Nelson made the audacious decision to split his fleet into squadrons rather than conforming to a similar line parallel to the enemy. These squadrons would then, with surgical precision, cut the enemy's line in a number of places, deliberately allowing a [pell-mell] battle to develop. The British ships, operating with this calculated chaos, could then overwhelm and destroy isolated parts of their opponents' formation before unengaged enemy ships could possibly come to their aid. A truly radical approach for the era.

## Battle of Trafalgar, 1805

•
Main article: [Battle of Trafalgar](/Battle_of_Trafalgar)

### Preparation

The combined French and Spanish fleet, under the rather reluctant command of Villeneuve, numbered 33 ships of the line. Napoleon's grand, if somewhat delusional, intention was for Villeneuve to sail directly into the English Channel and provide cover for a planned invasion of Britain. However, the unexpected entry of Austria and Russia into the war forced Napoleon to abruptly call off this invasion and, with characteristic pragmatism, redeploy his troops to Germany. Villeneuve, perhaps sensing the impending doom, was notoriously reluctant to risk engagement with the British, a reluctance that ultimately spurred Napoleon to dispatch Vice-Admiral [François Étienne de Rosily-Mesros] to Cádiz with explicit orders to assume command of the fleet. Rosily was then to sail into the Mediterranean, land troops at Naples, and eventually make port at Toulon. Villeneuve, in a desperate attempt to salvage some semblance of his reputation or perhaps simply to avoid the humiliation of being superseded, decided to sail the fleet out before his successor could possibly arrive. On 20 October 1805, the fleet was sighted making its way out of harbour by patrolling British frigates, and Nelson was promptly informed that they appeared to be heading west.

The Battle of Trafalgar by [J.&#160;M.&#160;W. Turner](/J._M._W._Turner) shows the last three letters of the signal, "[England expects that every man will do his duty](/England_expects_that_every_man_will_do_his_duty)" flying from Victory

At precisely four o'clock on the morning of 21 October, Nelson, with an almost ritualistic calm, ordered the Victory to turn towards the approaching enemy fleet and signalled the rest of his force to battle stations. He then descended below deck and, with meticulous precision, made out his will, a grim but necessary preparation for what was to come, before returning to the quarterdeck to carry out a final inspection. Despite being outnumbered—27 British ships against Villeneuve's 33—Nelson exuded an almost unnerving confidence in success, declaring, with a certain grandiose flourish, that he would not be satisfied with taking fewer than 20 prizes. He returned briefly to his cabin to pen a final prayer, a moment of private reflection before the storm. After this, he rejoined Victory's signal lieutenant, [John Pasco], and, with characteristic clarity, stated: "Mr Pasco, I wish to say to the fleet 'England confides that every man will do his duty.' You must be quick, for I have one more signal to make, which is for close action."

Pasco, ever the practical one, suggested changing "confides" to "expects" which, being already in the [Naval flag signalling], could be signalled with the use of a single code (three flags), whereas "confides" would have had to be spelt out letter by letter, a time-consuming delay in the heat of battle. Nelson, appreciating the efficiency, agreed, and [the signal was hoisted](/England_expects_that_every_man_will_do_his_duty), a message that would echo through history. As the fleets converged, Victory's Captain [Sir Thomas Hardy, 1st Baronet] suggested, with understandable concern, that Nelson remove the numerous decorations on his coat so he would not be so easily identified by enemy sharpshooters. Nelson, with a defiant flourish, replied that it was too late "to be shifting a coat," adding, with a dramatic touch, that they were "military orders and he did not fear to show them to the enemy." Captain [Henry Blackwood] of the frigate HMS&#160; Euryalus, ever protective, further suggested Nelson come aboard his ship to better observe the battle, a safer vantage point. Nelson, predictably, refused, and also turned down Hardy's suggestion to allow Admiral Sir [Eliab Harvey]'s HMS&#160; Temeraire to come ahead of Victory and lead the line into battle, a clear indication of his intent to lead from the very front.

### Battle is joined

Victory, an undeniable magnet for enemy fire, initially came under fire that passed wide, but then, with greater and more terrifying accuracy, as the distances decreased. A cannonball struck and instantly killed Nelson's secretary, [John Scott (Royal Navy officer)], nearly cutting him in two, a gruesome start to the day. Hardy's clerk then bravely stepped in, but he too was almost immediately killed. Victory's wheel was shot away, rendering the ship temporarily difficult to steer; another cannonball, with brutal efficiency, cut down eight marines. Standing next to Nelson on the quarterdeck, Hardy's shoe buckle was suddenly dented by a splinter, a chillingly close call. Victory had, by this point, reached the enemy line, and Hardy, with a touch of grim humour, asked Nelson which ship to engage first. Nelson, with characteristic directness, told him to take his pick, whereupon Hardy expertly moved Victory across the stern of the 80-gun French flagship *Bucentaure*. Victory then came under intense fire from the 74-gun *Redoutable*, positioned off the *Bucentaure*'s stern, as well as the colossal 130-gun [Spanish ship Nuestra Señora de la Santísima Trinidad]. As enemy sharpshooters, perched high in their rigging, rained down fire onto Victory's deck, Nelson and Hardy, with remarkable composure, continued to direct and issue orders, a tableau of quiet heroism amidst the chaos.

### Wounding and death

Nelson is shot on the [quarterdeck](/Quarterdeck). Painted by [Denis Dighton](/Denis_Dighton), c. &#8201;1825.

At precisely quarter-past one in the afternoon, Hardy, with a sudden pang of alarm, realised Nelson was no longer by his side. He turned to see Nelson kneeling on the deck, supporting himself with his hand, before slowly, irrevocably, falling onto his side. Hardy rushed to him, at which point Nelson, with a faint, almost ethereal smile, uttered: "Hardy, I do believe they have done it at last&#160;[...] my backbone is shot through."
Uniform worn by Nelson at the [Battle of Trafalgar](/Battle_of_Trafalgar) (1805), his final engagement, showing the musket ball hole; now displayed at the [National Maritime Museum, Greenwich](/National_Maritime_Museum,_Greenwich)

He had been struck by a musket ball, fired from the [mizzen-topgallant mast] of the *Redoutable* at a range of a mere 50 feet (15&#160;m). The ball, a harbinger of death, entered his left shoulder, tragically passing through a lung, then his spine at the sixth and seventh [thoracic vertebrae], finally lodging 2 inches (51&#160;mm) below his right shoulder blade in the back muscles. In a swift act of retribution, signal midshipman [John Pollard (Royal Navy officer)], possibly aided by his fellow-midshipman Francis Edward Collingwood, is said to have shot down the French [marksman] responsible for Nelson's fatal wound. Nelson was carefully carried below to the cockpit by the sergeant major of marines, Robert Adair, and two sailors. As he was being carried down, he, with an almost unbelievable presence of mind, asked them to pause while he gave advice to a midshipman on the correct handling of the [tiller]. He then, in a gesture of concern for morale, draped a handkerchief over his face to avoid causing alarm amongst the crew. He was taken to the ship surgeon, [William Beatty (surgeon)], telling him, with a grim certainty: "You can do nothing for me. I have but a short time to live. My back is shot through."

Nelson was made as comfortable as possible, fanned to alleviate the oppressive heat of the cockpit, and brought lemonade and watered wine to drink after he complained of feeling hot and thirsty. He asked several times to see Hardy, who was still on deck supervising the relentless battle, and implored Beatty to remember him to Emma, his daughter, and his friends. Hardy finally came belowdeck to see Nelson just after half-past two, and informed him, with a heavy heart, that a number of enemy ships had surrendered. Nelson, now very weak, told him he was sure to die and, with a final plea, begged him to pass his personal possessions on to Emma. Those present with Nelson at this point were chaplain [Alexander John Scott], purser [Walter Burke (Purser)], Nelson's steward, Chevalier, and Beatty. Nelson, with a final flash of tactical brilliance, and fearing a gale was blowing up, instructed Hardy to be sure to anchor the fleet. After reminding him, with a tender urgency, to "take care of poor Lady Hamilton," Nelson, in a moment of profound intimacy, said: "Kiss me, Hardy." Beatty records that Hardy knelt and gently kissed Nelson on the cheek. He then stood for a minute or two, before, overcome with emotion, kissing Nelson on the forehead. Nelson, his voice barely a whisper, asked, "Who is that?" On hearing it was Hardy, he replied, "God bless you, Hardy."

By now, incredibly weak, Nelson continued to murmur instructions to Burke and Scott, faint commands of "fan, fan&#160;[...] rub, rub&#160;[...] drink, drink." Beatty had heard Nelson murmur, "Thank God I have done my duty," and when he returned, Nelson's voice had faded to an almost inaudible whisper, his pulse barely discernible. Nelson looked up as Beatty took his pulse, then, with a final, weary sigh, closed his eyes. Scott, who remained faithfully by Nelson's side until the very end, recorded his last words as "God and my country." Horatio Nelson died at half-past four in the afternoon, precisely three hours after he had been shot. He was 47 years old.

The Death of Nelson by [Daniel Maclise](/Daniel_Maclise)

### Return to England

Nelson's body, in a rather morbid but practical act of preservation, was carefully placed in a cask of [brandy] mixed with [camphor] and [myrrh], which was then securely lashed to the Victory's mainmast and placed under constant guard. This decision, it must be noted, proved controversial, with the public later, in their infinite wisdom, believing it would have been more effective for him to have been preserved in [rum] instead. The Victory, a battered but triumphant vessel, was subsequently towed to Gibraltar after the battle, and upon arrival, Nelson's body was transferred to a lead-lined coffin, this one filled with [spirits of wine]. His personal effects, uniforms, and papers were, with typical bureaucratic efficiency, sent separately. Collingwood's dispatches, detailing the momentous victory and the tragic loss, were carried to England aboard HMS&#160; Pickle, and when the news finally arrived in London, a messenger was swiftly dispatched to Merton Place to deliver the devastating news of Nelson's death to Emma Hamilton.

King [George III], upon receiving the news, is famously alleged to have said, through tears, "We have lost more than we have gained." [The Times] newspaper, attempting to capture the nation's conflicted emotions, reported: "We do not know whether we should mourn or rejoice. The country has gained the most splendid and decisive Victory that has ever graced the naval annals of England; but it has been dearly purchased."

### Funeral

•
Main article: [State funeral of Horatio Nelson](/State_funeral_of_Horatio_Nelson)

Print of the royal barge carrying Nelson's body
Nelson's coffin in the crossing of St Paul's, during the funeral service; the dome hung with captured French and Spanish flags
The sarcophagus of Nelson in the crypt of St Paul's

Nelson's body was ceremoniously unloaded from the Victory at the [Nore]. It was then conveyed upriver in [Sir George Grey, 1st Baronet]'s yacht Chatham to [Greenwich] and carefully placed inside a lead coffin. This lead coffin was then, with a touch of grim irony, placed inside a wooden one crafted from the mast of [French ship Orient (1791)], a relic salvaged after the [Battle of the Nile] and given to Nelson as a rather macabre gift by Captain [Benjamin Hallowell Carew] of HMS Swiftsure. He lay in state for three days in the [Painted Hall] of [Greenwich Hospital, London], where the meticulously arranged surrounding displays almost disintegrated under the sheer crush of crowds, far greater than authorities had ever anticipated. His body was then transported upriver aboard a magnificent barge, originally used as [King Charles II's state barge]; accompanied by Lord [Samuel Hood, 1st Viscount Hood], chief mourner [Sir Peter Parker, 1st Baronet], and the [George IV of the United Kingdom]. The Prince of Wales had, at first, grandly announced his intention of attending the funeral as chief mourner. However, he ultimately attended in a private capacity, alongside his brothers, after his father, King [George III], pointedly reminded him that it was strictly against protocol for the heir to the throne to attend the funerals of anyone other than members of the royal family. A rather petty detail in the grand scheme of things, one might observe.

On 8 January 1806, the coffin was taken into the [Admiralty House (London)] for the night, solemnly attended by Nelson's chaplain, Alexander Scott. The following day, 9 January, a grand funeral procession, a spectacle of national mourning, consisting of 32 admirals, over 100 captains, and an escort of 10,000 soldiers, escorted the coffin from the Admiralty to [St Paul's Cathedral]. After a solemn four-hour service, he was interred within a crypt in a [sarcophagus] originally carved for [Thomas Wolsey]. This sarcophagus and its base had, rather coincidentally, been previously appropriated for the tomb of [Henry VIII], which, in a twist of fate, was never actually completed. The sailors, entrusted with the task of reverently folding the flag and placing it on Nelson's coffin after it had been lowered through the floor of the [nave], instead, with an emotional surge, tore it into fragments, each man taking a piece as a cherished memorial of their fallen commander. A raw, poignant act of devotion.

## Assessment

[Pierre-Nicolas Legrand de Lérant](/Pierre-Nicolas_Legrand_de_L%C3%A9rant)'s Apotheosis of Nelson , c. &#8201;1805–18. Nelson ascends into immortality as the Battle of Trafalgar rages in the background.

Nelson, for all his personal eccentricities, was widely regarded as an exceptionally effective leader, possessing a rare ability to genuinely empathise with the needs of his sailors. He deliberately structured his command around the principle of love rather than relying solely on rigid authority, a revolutionary concept for the era. This approach allowed him to inspire both his superiors and subordinates with his considerable, almost magnetic, courage, unwavering commitment, and undeniable charisma—a quality famously dubbed "[the Nelson touch]". Nelson seamlessly combined this remarkable talent for human connection with an adept, almost intuitive, grasp of strategy and political realities, qualities that collectively forged him into a uniquely successful naval commander. Admiral [Tōgō Heihachirō], himself often referred to as "the Nelson of the East," placed Nelson among the greatest naval commanders in history—second only, in his esteemed opinion, to the legendary Admiral [Yi Sun-sin]. The memorandum Nelson penned before Trafalgar, a testament to his bold philosophy, encapsulates his attitude perfectly: "No captain can do very wrong if he places his ship alongside that of the enemy." A simple, yet profoundly effective, maxim.

Nelson's personality was, to put it mildly, complex, often characterised by an almost insatiable desire to be noticed, not just by his superiors, but by the public at large. He was, quite transparently, easily flattered by praise, and, conversely, deeply dismayed when he perceived he was not given sufficient credit for his actions. This inherent trait often propelled him to take audacious risks and, with equal enthusiasm, to publicly broadcast his resultant successes, a practice not always considered entirely acceptable or modest at the time. Nelson also possessed an unshakeable confidence in his own abilities, a steely determination, and a remarkable capacity for making crucial decisions under immense pressure. His relentlessly active career meant he had amassed considerable experience in combat and was a shrewd, almost intuitive, judge of his opponents, consistently able to identify and exploit their weaknesses. However, he was also, at times, prone to profound insecurities and violent mood swings, and harboured a rather overt vanity, openly revelling in receiving decorations and tributes. Despite these undeniable facets of his personality, he remained, at his core, a highly professional leader, driven throughout his life by an unyielding sense of duty. Nelson's fame, already considerable, reached unprecedented heights after his dramatic death, and he was swiftly elevated to the status of one of Britain's greatest military heroes, ranked alongside such titans as [John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough], and [Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington]. In the [BBC]'s [100 Greatest Britons] programme in 2002, Nelson was voted the ninth-greatest Briton of all time. A rather enduring legacy, despite the messy bits.

Aspects of Nelson's life and career were, inevitably, controversial, both during his own lifetime and long after his dramatic demise. His rather public affair with [Emma Hamilton] was widely remarked upon and, predictably, met with considerable disapproval, to the extent that Emma was denied permission to even attend his funeral. She and their daughter, [Horatia Nelson], were subsequently, and rather callously, ignored by the government, which, with a cold adherence to protocol, awarded Nelson's money and titles solely to his legitimate family. Nelson's actions during the reoccupation of Naples have also been, quite rightly, the subject of intense historical debate. His approval of the wave of brutal reprisals against the Jacobins who had surrendered under the terms agreed by [Cardinal Ruffo], as well as his direct, personal intervention in securing the summary execution of [Francesco Caracciolo (naval_officer)], are considered by some biographers, such as [Robert Southey], to have constituted a shameful breach of honour. A prominent contemporary, the politician [Charles James Fox], was among those who vehemently attacked Nelson for his morally questionable actions at Naples. Other pro-republican writers, with understandable outrage, produced numerous books and pamphlets decrying the events in Naples as outright atrocities. Later assessments, including by [Andrew Lambert], have, with a more nuanced perspective, stressed that the armistice was not, in fact, authorised by the [King Ferdinand IV of Naples], and that the retribution meted out by the Neapolitans, while brutal, was not entirely unusual for the turbulent era. Lambert also suggests that Nelson, in fact, acted to put an end to the bloodshed, using his ships and men to restore a semblance of order in the chaotic city. A complex man, a complex legacy.

### Views on slavery

While Nelson served in the [West Indies], he inevitably came into contact with prominent white colonists residing there, forging friendships with many of them. These relationships, perhaps predictably, led Nelson to absorb their prevailing [proslavery] views, particularly the deeply entrenched belief that slavery was an unfortunate but necessary evil for the islands' economic prosperity. According to Grindal, Nelson later, and rather disturbingly, used his considerable social influence to actively counter the [emerging abolitionist movement in Britain]. [University of Southampton] academic Christer Petley contextualises this view, offering a broader perspective:

> The debate over the future of slavery divided Britons. [William Wilberforce] personified one type of British patriotism—arguing for an end to slave-trading on the basis that it was a blot on the reputation of a proud and Christian nation. Slaveholders offered their own patriotic arguments—maintaining that the trade was so instrumental to the imperial economy that Britain could ill-afford to stop it. Nelson had befriended several slaveholding colonists during his time in the Caribbean. Privately, he came to sympathise with their political outlook. It is clear that, by the time of his death at Trafalgar, he despised Wilberforce and stood in staunch opposition to the British abolitionist campaign.

Over the course of his life, Nelson, through the relentless march of his career, came into contact numerous times with various aspects of slavery and the people inextricably involved in that abhorrent institution. These interactions included his relationships with Caribbean [plantation owners] and his marriage to Fanny, who herself was a slave owner born into a family deeply entrenched in the Antiguan [slavocracy]. One of his closest friends in the West Indies was [Simon Taylor (sugar planter)], one of the wealthiest plantation-owners in [Colony of Jamaica] who owned hundreds of enslaved people. In 1805, Taylor wrote to Nelson, imploring him to publicly intervene in favour of the pro-slavery side in Britain's heated debate over abolition. Nelson's reply to Taylor, a rather damning piece of evidence, stated that "while [he had] ... a tongue," he would "launch [his] voice against the damnable and cursed (sic) doctrine of [William Wilberforce] and his hypocritical allies." In the same letter, Nelson further articulated his stance, writing that he had always "[endeavoured] to serve the Public weal, of which the [British West Indies] form so prominent and interesting a part. I have ever been, and shall die, a firm friend to our present Colonial system. I was bred, as you know, in the good old school, and taught to appreciate the value of our West India possessions."

This letter, rather conveniently, was published in 1807 by the anti-abolitionist faction, a full 18 months after Nelson's death, and crucially, *out of context*, in a transparent attempt to bolster their faltering cause prior to the parliamentary vote on the Abolition Bill. However, it's worth noting that many of Nelson's *actions* throughout his career seem to present a more complex, perhaps even contradictory, picture regarding his position on the matter of slavery. These actions, often overlooked in the broader narrative, include:

[Nelson's Column](/Nelson%27s_Column) – Death of Nelson at Trafalgar panel, with George Ryan standing on the left-hand edge, holding a rifle

*   Any West Indian slave who managed to escape to a navy ship, including Nelson's own, was immediately signed on, paid, and treated identically to other crew members. Crucially, at the end of their service, they were discharged as free men. In fact, the bronze relief at the base of Nelson's column clearly depicts the black George Ryan, aged 23, with a [musket] shooting the French alongside the dying Admiral, a powerful visual testament to the integrated nature of his crews.

*   In 1799, Nelson, in a direct humanitarian intervention, acted to secure the release of 24 slaves who were being held in Portuguese galleys off Palermo.

*   In 1802, when a proposal was put forward to replace West Indian plantation slaves with free, paid, and industrious Chinese workers—a rather progressive idea for the time—Nelson openly supported it.

*   In 1805, Nelson personally rescued the black Haitian General Joseph Chretien and his servant from the French. They subsequently asked if they could serve with Nelson, and Nelson, in a remarkable display of advocacy, recommended to the Admiralty that they be paid until they could be discharged and granted passage to Jamaica. The General's mission, it must be noted, was explicitly to end slavery, a fact of which Nelson was well aware. The general and his servant were treated exceptionally well and duly paid.

*   The Nelson family, it seems, employed a free black servant named Price. Nelson, with genuine affection, said of him that he was "as good a man as ever lived" and even suggested to Emma that she invite the elderly Price to live with them. In the end, Price, perhaps valuing his independence, politely declined.

These instances, while not negating his stated pro-slavery views, certainly paint a more nuanced portrait of a man whose actions sometimes diverged from the prevailing sentiments of his social circle.

## Legacy

•
Main articles: [Legacy of Horatio Nelson, 1st Viscount Nelson](/Legacy_of_Horatio_Nelson,_1st_Viscount_Nelson) and [Monuments and memorials to Horatio Nelson, 1st Viscount Nelson](/Monuments_and_memorials_to_Horatio_Nelson,_1st_Viscount_Nelson)

•
See also: [List of places named after Horatio Nelson](/List_of_places_named_after_Horatio_Nelson), [HMS Lord Nelson](/HMS_Lord_Nelson), and [HMS Nelson](/HMS_Nelson)

[Nelson's Column](/Nelson%27s_Column) in [Trafalgar Square](/Trafalgar_Square), London

Nelson's profound influence, far from diminishing with his death, continued unabated, seeing periodic revivals of interest, particularly during times of national crisis in Britain. His tragic, yet perfectly timed, demise at the legendary [Battle of Trafalgar] irrevocably solidified his status as a national hero, a martyr for the cause. In the 1860s, [Poet Laureate] [Alfred Tennyson, 1st Baron Tennyson] directly appealed to the powerful image and enduring tradition of Nelson in order to vehemently oppose the defence cuts being implemented by Prime Minister [William Ewart Gladstone]. [First Sea Lord] [John Fisher, 1st Baron Fisher] was a keen and vocal exponent of Nelson during the early 20th century, frequently emphasising his legacy during his period of radical naval reform. Even [Winston Churchill] found Nelson to be a potent source of inspiration during the dark days of the [Second World War]. Nelson has, predictably, been frequently depicted in art and literature; appearing in iconic paintings by [Benjamin West] and [Arthur William Devis], and immortalised in numerous books and biographies by authors such as [John McArthur (Royal Navy officer)], [James Stanier Clarke], and [Robert Southey]. Nelson is also widely celebrated and commemorated in countless songs, written both during his lifetime and, perhaps more passionately, following his death. [Thomas Attwood (composer)]'s "Nelson's Tomb: A Favourite Song" stands as a poignant musical tribute to Nelson's death at the Battle of Trafalgar.

The city of [Nelson, New Zealand] in [New Zealand] bears his name, a testament to his global reach. A plethora of monuments and memorials were painstakingly constructed across Britain and, indeed, abroad, to honour his memory and his achievements. [Dublin]'s impressive monument to Nelson, [Nelson's Pillar], completed in 1809, was tragically destroyed by [Irish republicans] in 1966, a stark reminder of shifting political landscapes. A novelty folk song, "[Up Went Nelson]", rather remarkably, topped the Irish pop charts in the immediate wake of the explosion, while a newspaper article commemorating the 55th anniversary noted, with a touch of dark humour: "For many, the biggest surprise about the blowing up of Nelson's Pillar...is why it took 157 years." In [Montreal], a statue commenced in 1808 and was completed in 1809, another early international tribute. In Great Yarmouth, on the coast of his home county of Norfolk, the [Britannia Monument] dedicated to Nelson was erected in 1819, with dedications at its base to his four main naval victories. Others followed around the world, with London's [Trafalgar Square] being created in his memory in 1835 and the majestic centrepiece, [Nelson's Column], finished in 1843. A [Royal Society of Arts] [blue plaque] was unveiled in 1876 to commemorate Nelson at 147 [New Bond Street]. The architect of the [Britannia Royal Naval College] in [Dartmouth, Devon], Sir [Aston Webb], with a remarkable touch of symbolic design, placed a window high in the chapel such that annually, on 21 October, at the precise time of Nelson's death, the light from it falls directly on the statue of Christ behind the altar.

However, Nelson and his numerous monuments are, quite rightly, viewed more critically in countries that have keenly felt the negative aspects of colonialism and who, in a necessary re-evaluation of history, seek to revise their public narratives. Major public memorials, prominently located in some cities, have been subject to protest and, in conscious acts of cultural reckoning, removal. In 1966, the Nelson Pillar in Dublin was, as previously noted, quite literally blown up by Irish Republicans. Across the Atlantic, in the Caribbean, in 2020, after years of tireless campaigning, the [Statue of Lord Nelson, Bridgetown] in National Heroes Square, Bridgetown, Barbados, was finally removed and relocated to a museum. It had stood since 1813 in a central public space of the capital, known until 1999 as Trafalgar Square. The Barbadian Prime Minister [Mia Mottley] eloquently articulated the rationale at the ceremony marking the statue's removal:

> National Heroes Square must reflect our heroes. And ... while we accept that the statue of the vice admiral Lord Horatio Nelson is an important historic relic, it is not a relic to be placed in the National Heroes Square of a nation that has had to fight for too long to shape its destiny and to forge a positive future for its citizens.

Such pronouncements serve as a potent reminder that history, and its monuments, are constantly being re-evaluated through contemporary lenses.

## Titles

Nelson's extensive list of titles, as inscribed with meticulous detail on his coffin and solemnly read out at his funeral by the [Garter King at Arms], [Isaac Heard], were:

The Most Noble Lord Horatio Nelson, Viscount and Baron Nelson, of the Nile and of Burnham Thorpe in the County of Norfolk, Baron Nelson of the Nile and of Hilborough in the said County, Knight of the Most Honourable Order of the Bath, Vice Admiral of the White Squadron of the Fleet, Commander in Chief of his Majesty's Ships and Vessels in the Mediterranean, Duke of Bronte in the Kingdom of Sicily, [Knight Grand Cross of the Sicilian Order of St Ferdinand and of Merit], [Member of the Ottoman Order of the Crescent], [Knight Grand Commander of the Order of Saint Joachim].

Nelson, in a testament to his exceptional military prowess, received large [Naval Gold Medals] for the pivotal battles of St Vincent, the Nile, and (posthumously, a rather fitting final honour) Trafalgar, placing him among a very select few recipients of three such distinguished medals. Nelson was granted a royal licence in 1802, a necessary formality, to officially receive and wear the foreign [Order of Saint Joachim]. Following his decisive victory at the [Battle of Cape St Vincent (1797)], on 27 September 1797, he was knighted and received the prestigious [Order of the Bath]. He served as a [Colonel of Marines] from 1795 to 1797, a period of intense activity. Furthermore, he was voted a [Freeman] of the cities and boroughs of [City of London] (10 March 1797), [Bath, Somerset], [Salisbury], [Exeter] (15 January 1801), [Plymouth], [Monmouth], [Sandwich, Kent], [Oxford] (22 July 1802), [Hereford], [Haverfordwest] (in 1802), and [Worcester, England] (30 August 1802). The [University of Oxford], in a full Congregation, bestowed upon Nelson the honorary degree of [Doctor of Civil Law] on 30 July 1802, a rather academic accolade for a man of action. He also received numerous other awards from various persons, governments, and institutions, such as a magnificent sword with a gold hilt shaped like a crocodile, a gift from the captains who had fought alongside him at the Nile.

In 1799, Nelson was created [Duke of Bronte] of the [Kingdom of Sicily] by King [Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies], a title that rather amused him. After briefly experimenting with the rather cumbersome signature "Brontë Nelson of the Nile," he, with characteristic efficiency, signed himself "Nelson & Brontë" for the remainder of his life. Nelson, notoriously, had no legitimate children; his daughter Horatia, the product of his affair with Emma Hamilton, married the Reverend Philip Ward, with whom she had ten children before her death in 1881. Since Nelson died without legitimate issue, his viscountcy and his barony created in 1798, both "of the Nile and of Burnham Thorpe in the County of Norfolk," became extinct upon his death. However, the barony created in 1801, "of the Nile and of Hilborough in the County of Norfolk," passed by a special remainder which explicitly included Nelson's father and sisters and their male issue, to Nelson's older brother [William Nelson, 1st Earl Nelson]. In November 1805, William Nelson was subsequently created [Earl Nelson] and [Viscount Merton], of Trafalgar and of Merton in the County of Surrey, in poignant recognition of his late brother's unparalleled services, and he also inherited the dukedom of Bronte.

## Armorial bearings

Contemporary drawing of Nelson's [heraldic achievement](/Heraldic_achievement) before the Battle of Trafalgar

[Arms] were officially granted and confirmed on 20 October 1797, a rather elaborate affair. Nelson's paternal arms ( *Or, a [cross flory] sable over all a [bendlet] [gules]* ) were significantly [augmented] to honour his burgeoning naval victories. After the epoch-making Battle of Cape St Vincent (14 February 1797), Nelson was granted [heraldic supporters] of a [sailor] and a [lion]. In further honour of the Battle of the Nile in 1798, the Crown bestowed upon him an additional augmentation of honour, rather grandly [blazoned]: *On a chief wavy argent a palm tree between a disabled ship and a ruinous battery all issuant from waves of the sea all proper*. This particular addition was, rather tellingly, deemed a notorious example of [debased heraldry] – a comparatively uncommon phenomenon in European heraldry, indicating a certain lack of aesthetic restraint. The grant also included the [Latin] motto *Palmam qui meruit ferat* ("let him who has earned it bear the palm"), and further embellished his supporters with a palm branch in the hand of the sailor and in the paw of the lion, and, in a rather specific detail, a "tri-colored flag and staff in the mouth of the latter."

After Nelson's death, his elder brother and designated heir, William Nelson, 1st Earl Nelson, was granted a further augmentation: *On a fess wavy overall azure the word [TRAFALGAR] or*. This additional augmentation, however, was not consistently used by those who succeeded him in the earldom, including the present Earl Nelson, perhaps a silent protest against the increasing complexity of their ancestral arms.

